const a = [
  {"id":1699,"text":"'Eggshell' calcification in the hilar lymph nodes is a feature of which of the following?","explanation":"The **'eggshell' calcification** in the hilar lymph nodes is a characteristic feature of silicosis.\r\n\r\n**Silicosis** is a form of pneumoconiosis caused by inhalation of crystalline silica particles, commonly found in occupations such as mining, sandblasting, and construction. Over time, these inhaled particles lead to the formation of fibrotic nodules in the lungs, known as silicotic nodules. In some cases, these nodules may undergo calcification, particularly in the hilar lymph nodes.\r\n\r\nThe term 'eggshell' calcification refers to a thin layer of calcification surrounding the hilar lymph nodes, which can be visualized on imaging studies such as chest X-rays or computed tomography (CT) scans. The presence of this characteristic calcification pattern in the hilar lymph nodes is strongly suggestive of silicosis.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 702.","responses":[{"text":"Byssinosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Berylliosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anthracosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silicosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1722,"text":"Which of the following drugs is a 5-lipoxygenase pathway inhibitor?","explanation":"The drug **zileuton** is a 5-lipoxygenase pathway inhibitor. The 5-lipoxygenase pathway plays a crucial role in the production of leukotrienes, which are inflammatory mediators involved in various allergic and inflammatory conditions, including asthma.\r\nBy blocking this pathway, it helps to alleviate inflammation and bronchoconstriction in conditions such as asthma.\r\n\r\nUnlike other asthma medications that primarily target bronchodilation or inflammation, Zileuton specifically targets the 5-lipoxygenase pathway, providing an alternative approach to managing asthma symptoms. It is usually prescribed as an adjunct therapy in patients who require additional control of their asthma symptoms despite using other asthma medications.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 712.","responses":[{"text":"Cromolyn","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monteluklast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zileuton","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Theophylline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Omalizumab","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1737,"text":"What is the most common cause of community-acquired pneumonia?","explanation":"The most common cause of community-acquired pneumonia is ***Streptococcus pneumoniae***. Streptococcus pneumoniae is a gram-positive bacterium that colonizes the upper respiratory tract and can cause infection when it enters the lower respiratory tract.\r\n\r\nOther pathogens such as *Mycoplasma pneumoniae, Legionella pneumophila, Klebsiella pneumoniae*, and *Staphylococcus aureus* can also cause community-acquired pneumonia, but Streptococcus pneumoniae is the most common causative agent.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 88.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klebsiella pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycoplasma pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1825,"text":"A medicolegal doctor is called to perform a post-mortem examination. He gives an incision starting from one inch below the symphysis menti up to symphysis pubis without cutting the umbilicus. What is this incision called?","explanation":"The incision described, starting from one inch below the symphysis menti (chin) up to the symphysis pubis without cutting the umbilicus, is called an **I-shaped incision**. This incision is commonly used in forensic medicine and post-mortem examinations.\r\n\r\nThe I-shaped incision allows for easy access to the thoracic and abdominal cavities for examination of organs and structures. The incision begins at the chin and extends vertically down to the pubic region, following the midline of the body. By avoiding the umbilicus, it allows for a clear view and access to the organs without interfering with the abdominal structures.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 102.","responses":[{"text":"Y-shaped incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-shaped incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"I-shaped incision","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cruciate incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified Y-shaped- incision","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1832,"text":"A 45-year-old female presents to the outpatient department with progressive shortness of breath and dry cough. She has a history of joint pain and red eyes as well. Chest X-ray shows bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, widespread pulmonary lines, and honeycombing. Which of the following would the patient be suffering from?","explanation":"**Sarcoidosis** is a multisystem inflammatory disease that primarily affects the lungs and lymph nodes. It can also involve other organs such as the skin, eyes, heart, and joints. The condition is characterized by the formation of **non-caseating granulomas**, which are small clusters of immune cells, in affected tissues.\r\n\r\nThe **bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy, widespread pulmonary lines (reticular shadowing)**, and **honeycombing** seen on the chest X-ray are consistent with the characteristic radiographic findings of sarcoidosis. The presence of joint pain and red eyes further supports the diagnosis, as these extrapulmonary manifestations are commonly associated with sarcoidosis.","reference":"1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 694.\r\n\r\n\r\n2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 610.\r\n\r\n3) Bokhari SRA, Zulfiqar H, Mansur A. Sarcoidosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 17, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430687/","responses":[{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumoconiosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryptogenic fibrosing alveolitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1835,"text":"A 12-year-old boy came to the emergency department with complaints of abrupt onset of high fever with shaking chills, productive cough, and mucopurulent sputum. On gram stain, numerous pus cells with gram-positive lancet-shaped diplococci were observed. Which of the following is the most likely organism?","explanation":"The most likely organism causing the infection in the 12-year-old boy is ***Streptococcus pneumoniae***. *Streptococcus pneumoniae* is a gram-positive bacterium that commonly causes **community-acquired pneumonia** in children and adults. \r\n\r\nIt is characterized by **lancet-shaped diplococci**, and the presence of numerous pus cells suggests an inflammatory response to the infection. Streptococcus pneumoniae is a common cause of bacterial pneumonia and is known to produce symptoms such as high fever, shaking chills, productive cough, and mucopurulent sputum.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 119.","responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophila","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilus influenzae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Moraxella catarrhalis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1839,"text":"A 4-year-old boy has a 1-month history of recurrent cough with wheezing. There is no history of previous similar complaints and no family history of asthma or tuberculosis. Examination shows enlarged cervical nodes and bronchi. Chest X-Ray shows air trapping on the right side during inspiration. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"In a 4-year-old boy with a 1-month history of recurrent cough with wheezing, enlarged cervical nodes, and findings of air trapping on chest X-ray, the most likely diagnosis is **foreign body aspiration**.\r\n\r\nForeign body aspiration occurs when a foreign object enters the airway and obstructs the bronchi, leading to respiratory symptoms such as cough, wheezing, and difficulty breathing. It commonly occurs in young children who tend to explore objects by putting them in their mouths.\r\n\r\nThe presence of wheezing and air trapping on the right side during inspiration suggests partial obstruction of the right main bronchus, causing air to be trapped in the affected lung segment.\r\n\r\nEnlarged cervical nodes may indicate reactive lymphadenopathy due to the presence of an inflammatory process in the airways.\r\n\r\nA thorough history, clinical examination, and imaging findings support the diagnosis of foreign body aspiration in this case. Prompt evaluation and appropriate intervention, such as bronchoscopy, are necessary to remove the foreign object and relieve the obstruction.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: \r\n669, 671, 683.","responses":[{"text":"Nodal tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foreign body aspiration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Right middle lobe syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastro esophageal reflux","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reactive airway disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1841,"text":"A 3-year-old boy is brought with complaints of difficulty in breathing, noisy harsh sounds produced during inspiration, and high-grade fever for 2 days. What will be the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"Based on the symptoms described (difficulty in breathing, noisy harsh sounds during inspiration, and high-grade fever), the most likely diagnosis in this case is **epiglottitis**. Epiglottitis is an inflammation of the epiglottis, a flap of tissue that covers the entrance of the trachea during swallowing to prevent food and liquid from entering the airway. It is commonly caused by a bacterial infection, most commonly by ***Haemophilus influenzae*** **type B (Hib)** bacteria.\r\n\r\nEpiglottitis is a serious condition that can rapidly progress and cause airway obstruction, leading to respiratory distress.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 85.","responses":[{"text":"Foreign body inhalation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial tracheitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epiglottitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Laryngitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute laryngotracheobronchitis (croup)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1842,"text":"A 6-year-old male child is brought to the emergency room because of recurrent wheezing. He is on inhaled steroids. His mother gives a history that he has daytime symptoms\u003e 2/week and nighttime symptoms \u003e 2/months. On spirometry, his FEV is \u003e 80% with a PEF variability of 30%. He gets diagnosed with asthma. What is the classification of severity of asthma in this patient?","explanation":"The classification of asthma severity is based on the frequency and severity of symptoms, as well as lung function measurements. In this case, the child has daytime symptoms more than two times per week and nighttime symptoms more than two times per month, which places him in the category of persistent asthma.\r\n\r\nThe spirometry results show that his forced expiratory volume (FEV) is greater than 80%, indicating mild airflow limitation. The peak expiratory flow (PEF) variability of 30% suggests some variability in lung function.\r\n\r\nAccording to the Global Initiative for Asthma (GINA) guidelines, **mild persistent asthma** is characterized by symptoms occurring more than twice a week, but not daily, and nighttime symptoms more than twice a month. Lung function measurements, such as FEV, are usually greater than 80%, and PEF variability is greater than 20% but less than 30%.","reference":"1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 530.\r\n\r\n2) Dusser D, Montani D, Chanez P, et al. Mild asthma: an expert review on epidemiology, clinical characteristics and treatment recommendations. Allergy.","responses":[{"text":"Severe persistent asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cough variant asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mild intermittent asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Moderate persistent asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mild persistent asthma","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1843,"text":"A 6-year-old child has a sudden onset of dyspnea with wheezing. On physical examination, he is afebrile but has absent breath sounds on the right. His temperature = 37 °C, pulse \r\n= 82/minute, respiratory rate = 28/minute, and blood pressure = 100/60 mm Hg. An arterial blood gas measurement shows pO2 = 95 mm Hg, pCO2 = 25 mm Hg, and pH = 7.55. Following the administration of 100% FiO2 by nasal canula, a repeat measurement shows pO2 = 95 mm Hg, pCO2 = 25 mm Hg, and pH = 7.55. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis in this case is **foreign body aspiration**. The sudden onset of **dyspnea with wheezing, absent breath sounds on one side**, and the absence of fever suggests a localized obstruction of the airway. Foreign body aspiration occurs when an object is inhaled into the airway, leading to partial or complete blockage of the bronchus. This can cause localized wheezing and decreased breath sounds on the affected side.\r\n\r\nThe arterial blood gas measurement showing normal oxygenation (pO2 = 95 mm Hg) and low carbon dioxide levels (pCO2 = 25 mm Hg) indicates a ventilation-perfusion mismatch, which is commonly seen in cases of airway obstruction.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 671.","responses":[{"text":"Paraseptal emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Foreign body aspiration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboembolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchial asthma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1845,"text":"A middle-aged male presents with a two-week history of severe shortness of breath and fever. On examination, he is cyanosed with bilateral coarse crepitations all over the chest. Chest X-Ray shows bilateral lung infiltrates, with O2 saturation of 88% on room air. What is the next best investigation as part of management?","explanation":"The next best investigation as part of the management in this case would be a **high-resolution CT (HRCT) scan**.\r\n\r\nThe clinical presentation of severe shortness of breath, fever, bilateral lung infiltrates, and low oxygen saturation raises suspicion of a significant lung pathology such as diffuse parenchymal lung disease. HRCT is a valuable imaging modality that provides detailed and high-resolution images of the lung parenchyma, allowing for the evaluation of lung architecture and identification of specific abnormalities. It can help differentiate between different lung conditions, such as pneumonia, interstitial lung disease, or pulmonary edema, which may present with similar clinical features.\r\n\r\nHRCT is particularly useful in this case because it can provide additional information about the extent and distribution of the lung infiltrates, the presence of any underlying lung pathology, and help guide further management decisions. It can also assist in the diagnosis of specific conditions, such as identifying characteristic patterns in interstitial lung diseases.","reference":"1) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 605.\r\n\r\n2) Masood I, Elyassi W, Rind W. Medicine. 3rd ed. Majeed Sons; 2018: 241.","responses":[{"text":"ESR and CRP","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial blood gases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High resolution CT","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchoscopy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1848,"text":"A 20-year-old thin, tall boy presented to the emergency room with sudden onset of cough, severe shortness of breath, and chest pain. He recently arrived from the USA after a 16-hour flight. Immediate chest X-Ray was advised with the suspicion of pneumothorax. Which chest examination finding best reveals pneumothorax?","explanation":"The finding that best reveals **pneumothorax** on chest examination is a hyper-resonant percussion note on the affected side.\r\n\r\nPercussion is a technique used to assess the underlying structures and air content in the lungs. In a normal lung, percussion produces a resonant sound. However, in the case of pneumothorax, where air accumulates in the pleural space, the affected lung becomes hyperinflated and less dense, resulting in a **hyper-resonant percussion note**. This means that the sound produced on percussion is louder and more resonant than expected.\r\n\r\nOther findings that may be present in pneumothorax include decreased breath sounds on auscultation on the affected side due to reduced air entry, and decreased chest movements on the affected side due to lung collapse.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 706.","responses":[{"text":"Resonant percussion note on the affected side","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased chest movements on the affected side","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dull percussion note on the affected side","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased breath sounds on auscultation on the affected side","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyper-resonant percussion note on the affected side","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1852,"text":"A 50-year-old male patient presents to the outpatient clinic with shortness of breath which is gradual in onset along with dry cough for the last 5 years. On examination, there is the clubbing of fingers and bilateral basal end respiratory crackles are audible. Chest X-Ray shows bilateral lower lobe subpleural reticular shadowing. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis** is a chronic progressive lung disease characterized by the formation of fibrotic tissue in the lungs. It predominantly affects older individuals and commonly presents with symptoms such as shortness of breath, dry cough, and fatigue. Clubbing of the fingers is also a characteristic finding in IPF.\r\n\r\nOn examination, bilateral basal end inspiratory crackles are commonly heard in patients with IPF. These crackles represent the sound of fibrotic lung tissue rubbing against each other during inspiration.\r\n\r\nChest X-ray findings of bilateral lower lobe subpleural reticular shadowing are also consistent with IPF. Reticular shadowing refers to a pattern of fine linear opacities that resemble a network or reticulum, and it is commonly seen in IPF.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 606.","responses":[{"text":"Rheumatoid lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphangitis carcinomatosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersensitivity pneumonitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":1896,"text":"A 4-year-old boy is brought to you with complaints of fever and cough, persistent for the past 6 weeks, and has lost his weight in this period. On examination, of the chest, crepitations and a wheeze are audible on the right side of the chest. Labs show hemoglobin (Hb) of 9 gm/dl, erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) of 60 mm/hr, and induration in Mycobacterium tuberculin (MT) test is 11 mm. How will you treat?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms of fever, cough, and weight loss, along with the presence of crepitations and a wheeze on chest examination, raise suspicion for **tuberculosis (TB)**. The induration of 11 mm in the tuberculin (MT) test is significant and supports the diagnosis of TB.\r\n\r\nIn children, the standard treatment for active pulmonary tuberculosis is a combination of multiple antituberculous drugs for a duration of 6 months. The regimen typically includes **isoniazid, rifampicin, pyrazinamide**, and **ethambutol**. This multidrug therapy is effective in treating TB and preventing the development of drug resistance.\r\n\r\nThe use of broad-spectrum antibiotics or antipyretics alone would not be appropriate for the management of tuberculosis. Tuberculosis requires specific antituberculous therapy to eradicate the infection and prevent complications.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 593.","responses":[{"text":"6 months of antituberculous therapy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"12 months of antituberculous therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antipyretic with antiallergy for 6 months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Broad spectrum antibiotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Broad spectrum antibiotic with antipyretic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1915,"text":"What is the amount of air a person can breathe in beginning at the normal expiratory level and distending the lungs to the maximum amount?","explanation":"The **inspiratory capacity** is a measurement of lung volume that represents the maximum volume of air a person can inspire after a normal expiration.\r\n\r\nThe inspiratory capacity is calculated by adding the tidal volume (the volume of air inspired and expired during normal breathing) to the inspiratory reserve volume (the additional volume of air that can be inhaled after a normal inspiration).\r\n\r\nThe inspiratory capacity provides valuable information about lung function and respiratory health. It is often measured during pulmonary function tests to assess lung volumes and capacities, diagnose respiratory conditions, and monitor disease progression or response to treatment.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 688.","responses":[{"text":"Total lung capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expiratory capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inspiratory capacity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Functional residual capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vital capacity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1916,"text":"The DNA damage due to radicals formed as a result of radiation is an example of which of the following?","explanation":"The DNA damage caused by radicals formed as a result of radiation is an example of **indirect damage**. Indirect damage refers to the damage caused by the reactive intermediates generated by the interaction of radiation with molecules in the body, rather than direct interaction between the radiation and DNA.\r\n\r\nWhen ionizing radiation interacts with water molecules in the body, it produces free radicals, such as hydroxyl radicals (·OH), which are highly reactive and can cause oxidative damage to DNA. These free radicals can directly attack the DNA molecule, leading to DNA strand breaks, base modifications, and other types of DNA damage.\r\n\r\nThe DNA damage caused by these radicals can have various biological consequences, including cell death, mutations, and potentially the development of cancer.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 429.","responses":[{"text":"Direct damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indirect damage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Splitting of chemical bonds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Threshold level damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accidental damage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1923,"text":"A medico-legal doctor is performing the autopsy for the opening of the skull during post-mortem in a newborn baby. How should the incision be done?","explanation":"During the autopsy of a newborn baby, the incision for opening the skull is typically done by opening the **sagittal and coronal sutures**. The sagittal suture is the main suture that runs along the midline of the skull from the anterior fontanelle (soft spot) to the posterior fontanelle. The coronal suture runs horizontally from one side of the skull to the other.\r\n\r\nTo open the skull, the medico-legal doctor makes a cut along the sagittal suture and then continues the incision along the coronal suture. This allows for a flap-like opening of the skull, providing access to the brain and its structures.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 321.","responses":[{"text":"Cutting along sagittal sutures","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Over the top of the head from right ear to the left ear","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening of sagittal + coronal sutures","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Making a circular cut","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cutting from mastoid to mastoid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1924,"text":"The most important difference between a forensic autopsy and a pathological autopsy is that in forensic autopsy:","explanation":"The most important difference between a forensic autopsy and a pathological autopsy is that a forensic autopsy is a **valid documentary evidence in the court of law**. Forensic autopsies are performed in cases of unnatural, sudden, or suspicious deaths with the primary purpose of gathering evidence and determining the cause and manner of death. The findings and documentation from a forensic autopsy can be presented as evidence in legal proceedings.\r\n\r\nWhile both forensic and pathological autopsies involve the examination of the deceased, the focus and objectives differ. Pathological autopsies are primarily performed to study the underlying disease processes and understand the cause of death for medical and research purposes. In contrast, forensic autopsies are conducted within a legal framework to investigate potential crimes, determine the cause of death, identify any injuries or signs of foul play, and provide expert testimony in legal proceedings.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 98.","responses":[{"text":"Done in cases of unnatural sudden or suspicious deaths","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All cavities are opened even if injury is not found","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a valid documentary evidence in the court of law","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cause of death is usually not known but has to be determined","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External findings are of vital importance","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":1925,"text":"What is the main advantage of R. Virchow's technique of autopsy?","explanation":"The main advantage of Rudolf Virchow's technique of autopsy is that **each organ can be studied in detail**. Virchow's technique, also known as the \"systematic autopsy,\" emphasizes a thorough examination of each organ system to identify and document any abnormalities or pathological changes. This meticulous approach allows for a comprehensive understanding of the disease processes and contributes to accurate diagnosis and research.\r\n\r\nBy carefully examining each organ and its anatomical structures, such as blood vessels, tissues, and cellular components, Virchow's technique enables the pathologist to identify and analyze specific lesions, tumors, inflammatory changes, and other abnormalities. This detailed examination helps in establishing the cause of death, understanding the underlying disease processes, and providing valuable information for clinical management, research, and teaching purposes.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 103","responses":[{"text":"Body can be made available to relatives in 30 minutes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Preservation of anatomico-pathologic relationship","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spread of infection (HIV, HCV) can be limited","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Each organ can be studied in detail","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Preservation of vascular supply in pathological lesions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2228,"text":"Which of the following most commonly results in violent asphyxia deaths?","explanation":"**Mechanical asphyxia** is the most common cause of **violent asphyxia deaths**. Mechanical asphyxia occurs when the airway is physically obstructed, preventing the individual from breathing adequately. Examples of mechanical asphyxia include suffocation, strangulation, and compression of the chest or neck. These forms of asphyxia typically result from external forces applied to the body, such as ligature strangulation, manual strangulation, or chest compression. \r\n\r\nPathological asphyxia, environmental asphyxia, iatrogenic asphyxia, and toxic asphyxia are distinct categories of asphyxia but are less commonly associated with violent deaths compared to mechanical asphyxia.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 160.","responses":[{"text":"Pathological asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mechanical asphyxia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Toxic asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Environmental asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iatrogenic asphyxia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2386,"text":"A medico-legal doctor was called by the state law authorities to perform an autopsy on a suspected poisoning case. A detailed study of the stomach and its contents is usually done by which of the following?","explanation":"In a medico-legal autopsy, when a suspected poisoning case is being investigated, a detailed study of the stomach and its contents is usually done by **opening along the greater curvature**. \r\n\r\nOpening the stomach along the greater curvature allows for a thorough examination of the stomach's contents, including any ingested substances or potential toxicants. This approach provides a larger and more accessible area for examination and sampling of the stomach contents.\r\n\r\nBy opening along the greater curvature, the forensic pathologist can carefully inspect the contents, document any abnormalities, and collect samples for further analysis, such as toxicological testing. This technique ensures a comprehensive evaluation of the stomach, aiding in the identification of potential poisoning or other related pathological findings.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 104.","responses":[{"text":"Opening by incision on its anterior wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening along the lesser curvature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening along the greater curvature","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Opening by a transverse incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Can be opened by any side","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2387,"text":"A 9-month-old child is brought to the clinic for the assessment of cough. On examination, his respiratory rate (R/R) is 52 breaths/minute with no chest retractions and no wheeze on auscultation. How will this child be classified according to Integrated Management of Newborn and Childhood Illnesses (IMNCI)?","explanation":"A 9-month-old child presenting with a cough and a respiratory rate of 52 breaths per minute is consistent with the Integrated Management of Newborn and Childhood Illnesses (IMNCI) guidelines for **pneumonia** assessment. The IMNCI guidelines consider a fast breathing rate (50 breaths per minute or more) in children under 12 months as an important indicator of pneumonia. In addition, the absence of chest retractions and wheezing suggests a milder form of pneumonia.\r\n\r\nAccording to the IMNCI classification, the child's presentation would be categorized as \"Pneumonia.\" This classification is based on the presence of a cough and a fast breathing rate, which are key symptoms considered in the IMNCI guidelines for respiratory illnesses in children.","reference":"INTEGRATED MANAGEMENT OF NEONATAL \u0026 CHILDHOOD ILLNESS. Published 2017. https://phkh.nhsrc.pk/sites/default/files/2020-02/IMNCI%20Chartbooklet%20Pakistan%202017.pdf","responses":[{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Very severe disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cough and cold","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2390,"text":"In a putrefied body death resulted from drowning, diatoms are found in which of the following organs/viscera?","explanation":"In cases of death resulting from drowning, the presence of diatoms in specific organs/viscera can be helpful in establishing the cause of death. Diatoms are microscopic aquatic organisms that can enter the body during submersion in water and become trapped in various tissues.\r\n\r\nThe correct answer is **Brain and bone marrow**. Diatoms can be found in the brain and bone marrow due to their high vascularity and ability to accumulate diatoms during the drowning process. The presence of diatoms in these tissues provides strong evidence supporting death by drowning.\r\n\r\n- Hilum of right lung and right ear: While diatoms can enter the respiratory system during drowning, they are not typically found in the hilum of the lung or the ear.\r\n- Stomach and left lung: Diatoms are not commonly found in the stomach or the left lung.\r\n- Gall bladder and liver: Diatoms do not typically accumulate in the gall bladder or the liver.\r\n- Ileum and under surface of liver: These locations are not known to be associated with diatom accumulation in cases of drowning.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 182.","responses":[{"text":"Gall bladder and liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain and bone marrow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stomach and left lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileum and under surface of liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hilum of right lung and right ear","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2400,"text":"If pulmonary function test shows FEV1/FVC ratio is more than 0.70 with decreased total lung capacity (TLC), then the interpretation would be:","explanation":"Interpreting pulmonary function tests involves assessing different parameters to identify patterns and abnormalities in lung function. In this case, a decreased total lung capacity (TLC) along with an FEV1/FVC ratio of more than 0.70 indicates a **restrictive pattern**. A restrictive lung disease is characterized by reduced lung volumes and limited expansion of the lungs.","reference":"Le T, Vikas Bhushan. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2021. 31st ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 699.","responses":[{"text":"Obstructive pattern","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-specific reductions in FEV1 and FVC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed pattern","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Restrictive pattern","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2572,"text":"Which of the following is the correct Light's criteria for LDH serum ratio in exudative pleural effusion?","explanation":"According to Light's criteria, a **pleural effusion** is considered **exudative** if at least one of the following criteria is met:\r\n\r\n- Pleural fluid protein/serum protein ratio greater than 0.5\r\n- Pleural fluid LDH/serum LDH ratio greater than 0.6\r\n- Pleural fluid LDH level greater than two-thirds the upper limit of normal for serum LDH\r\n\r\nThe pleural fluid LDH/serum LDH ratio should be greater than 0.6 IU/ml to classify the pleural effusion as exudative.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 564.","responses":[{"text":"Greater than 0.5 IU/ml","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Greater than 0.6 IU/ml","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 0.4 IU/ml","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 0.6 IU/ml","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less than 0.5 IU/ml","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2573,"text":"Which of the following is the most common causative organism of pneumonia caused due to faulty air conditioning?","explanation":"The most common causative organism of pneumonia caused due to faulty air conditioning is ***Legionella pneumophila***. Legionella is a type of bacteria that can grow and multiply in water systems, including cooling towers, hot tubs, and **air conditioning systems**. When these systems are not properly maintained or cleaned, Legionella bacteria can be released into the air and inhaled, leading to **Legionnaires' disease**, which is a severe form of pneumonia. \r\n\r\nOther organisms listed, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa, Mycoplasma pneumoniae, Staphylococcus aureus*, and *Klebsiella pneumoniae*, may also cause pneumonia in different settings, but they are not specifically associated with pneumonia caused by faulty air conditioning.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 141.","responses":[{"text":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klebsiella pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycoplasma pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophila","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2657,"text":"Which of the following drugs is a mast cell stabilizer?","explanation":"**Cromoglicic acid** is a medication that helps prevent the release of inflammatory substances, such as histamine, from mast cells. It is commonly used in the treatment of asthma and allergic conditions, including allergic rhinitis and allergic conjunctivitis.\r\n\r\nLoratadine, clemastine, chlorpheniramine, and diphenhydramine, are antihistamines that block the effects of histamine after it has been released. While they can help relieve allergy symptoms, they do not directly stabilize mast cells like cromoglicic acid.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 416.","responses":[{"text":"Cromoglicic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Loratadine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphenhydramine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlorpheniramine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clemastine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2670,"text":"Which of the following arteries is most commonly blocked in autopsy in case of coronary atherosclerosis?","explanation":"The most commonly blocked artery in cases of coronary atherosclerosis is the **left anterior descending artery (LAD)**. The LAD supplies a large portion of the left ventricle, including the anterior wall, septum, and apex of the heart. It is a major branch of the left coronary artery and is susceptible to plaque buildup and narrowing, leading to reduced blood flow and potentially causing a heart attack.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 132.","responses":[{"text":"Right marginal artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left subclavian artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Circumflex artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left anterior descending artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2742,"text":"Which of the following is correct regarding the dissection of the heart during autopsy?","explanation":"During the dissection of the heart in an autopsy, the correct approach is to **open the heart in the direction of blood** flow. This means that the dissection starts from the atria and progresses to the ventricles, following the path of blood flow through the heart.\r\n\r\nOpening the heart in the direction of blood flow allows for a systematic examination of the internal structures and chambers, ensuring a thorough assessment of any abnormalities or pathological changes. By following the natural flow of blood, the pathologist can observe the valves, assess the thickness of the myocardium, inspect the coronary arteries, and examine the internal structures of the heart in a logical sequence.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 106.","responses":[{"text":"Both chambers are opened together","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opposite to the direction of blood flow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The direction and order does not matter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In the direction of blood flow","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The ventricle is opened first, followed by the atrium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2759,"text":"Which of the following organs is not dissected in detail during autopsy?","explanation":"During an autopsy, the **spinal cord** is not typically dissected in detail. The focus of an autopsy is primarily on examining the organs and tissues within the body to determine the cause of death and any underlying diseases or conditions. While the brain, lungs, kidneys, and heart are commonly examined during an autopsy, the spinal cord is not routinely dissected unless there is a specific indication to do so, such as suspected spinal cord injury or disease.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 110.","responses":[{"text":"Lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidneys","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spinal cord","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":2809,"text":"Why is dextromethorphan an antitussive drug?","explanation":"**Dextromethorphan** is an **antitussive** drug because it increases the threshold for cough. Coughing is a reflex mechanism initiated by stimulation of cough receptors in the airways. These receptors can be triggered by various factors such as irritants, inflammation, or excess mucus production.\r\n\r\nDextromethorphan acts on the cough center in the brain, specifically the medullary cough center, and raises the threshold at which the brain responds to the cough reflex. By increasing this threshold, dextromethorphan reduces the frequency and intensity of coughing. It does not directly suppress the production of mucus or reduce the underlying cause of coughing but instead provides temporary relief by reducing the urge to cough.","reference":"Antitussive agent - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed May 12, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/antitussive-agent","responses":[{"text":"It inhibits the activity of cilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It increases the intensity of dry cough","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It reduces productive cough","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It increases the threshold for cough","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is an NMDA receptor agonist","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":2811,"text":"A physician prescribed an anti-tuberculosis drug to a patient. He started feeling a tingling sensation. What could you give to reverse this effect?","explanation":"The likely cause of paresthesia and tingling sensation in the hands and feet in this patient receiving anti-tuberculosis therapy (ATT) is **peripheral neuritis**. Peripheral neuritis refers to inflammation of the peripheral nerves, and it can be a side effect of **isoniazid**, which is commonly used in ATT regimens for tuberculosis.\r\n\r\nTo prevent or manage peripheral neuritis associated with isoniazid therapy, it is recommended to supplement with **pyridoxine (vitamin B6)** concurrently. This helps to counteract the deficiency and reduce the risk of nerve damage.\r\n\r\nIsoniazid is known to cause peripheral neuropathy, particularly due to its effect on vitamin B6 (pyridoxine) metabolism. Isoniazid can lead to pyridoxine deficiency, which is essential for nerve function and maintenance. The deficiency of pyridoxine can result in nerve damage, leading to symptoms such as paresthesia, tingling, and sensory disturbances in the hands and feet.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 65.","responses":[{"text":"Folate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B6","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin A","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10424,"text":"What is the concentration of oxygen in air?","explanation":"The concentration of oxygen in the air is approximately **20.9%**. The Earth's atmosphere is composed of various gases, with oxygen being one of the most important for supporting life. In the atmosphere, oxygen exists as diatomic oxygen molecules (O2). This concentration of oxygen is considered optimal for normal respiratory function and is necessary for sustaining human and animal life.\r\n\r\nIt's worth noting that the remaining composition of air primarily consists of nitrogen (approximately 78%) and traces of other gases such as carbon dioxide, argon, and water vapor. These gases play important roles in various physiological and environmental processes.","reference":"Wuthichotwanichgij G, Geater AF. Low-oxygen atmosphere and its predictors among agricultural shallow wells in northern thailand. Safety and Health at Work. Published March 2015. Accessed June 14, 2023. https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S2093791114000808","responses":[{"text":"0.25%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"61%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.0325%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20.9%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"78%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10457,"text":"Which of the following findings in a body confirms death by drowning upon postmortem examination?","explanation":"The presence of **diatoms in the brain and kidney** is a significant finding in postmortem examination that confirms death by drowning. Diatoms are microscopic aquatic algae that can be inhaled or ingested by an individual when submerged in water. During drowning, these diatoms can enter the bloodstream and settle in various organs, including the brain and kidney.\r\n\r\nDiatom analysis involves the microscopic examination of these algae in tissue samples obtained during autopsy. The presence of diatoms in the brain and kidney suggests that the individual was alive at the time of submersion and inhaled or ingested water, leading to drowning.\r\n\r\nOther findings such as oronasal froth, ballooning or voluminous lungs, and cutis anserina (goosebumps) can also be associated with drowning but are not specific to drowning alone.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 202.","responses":[{"text":"Oronasal froth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ballooning or voluminous lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diatoms in brain and kidney","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cutis anserina","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11729,"text":"Compared to an abstract, a synopsis does not have which of the following?","explanation":"Compared to an abstract, a **synopsis does not typically include the results** of the study. A synopsis provides a concise summary of a research study or project, highlighting its key aspects and findings. While an abstract usually includes the main findings or results of a study, a synopsis focuses more on the background, objective, methods, and significance of the research. It serves as a brief overview or outline of the study, allowing readers to quickly grasp the main points without going into extensive detail.\r\n\r\nIn a synopsis, the introduction provides background information about the topic, the objective statement states the purpose of the study, the sample size describes the number of participants or subjects included, and the hypothesis presents the expected outcome or relationship being tested. However, the detailed results and statistical analyses are typically omitted from a synopsis, as it aims to provide a concise summary rather than a comprehensive report.","reference":"Difference between abstract and summary. Pediaa. Published January 8, 2016. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://pediaa.com/difference-between-abstract-and-summary/","responses":[{"text":"Introduction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Objective statement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Result","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sample size","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11730,"text":"Non intrusive form of autopsy in which computed tomography (CT scan) and magnified resonance imaging (MRI) are used is known as?","explanation":"The non-intrusive form of autopsy that utilizes computed tomography (CT scan) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is known as **virtopsy**. Virtopsy combines advanced imaging techniques with traditional forensic methods to perform a comprehensive examination of the body without the need for conventional autopsy procedures. It allows for detailed visualization and analysis of the internal structures, organs, and tissues, providing valuable information about the cause of death and any associated injuries or pathologies.\r\n\r\nVirtopsy offers several advantages over traditional autopsies, including the preservation of the body's integrity, non-destructiveness, and the ability to capture high-resolution images for further analysis. It can help in identifying traumatic injuries, detecting hidden internal injuries, assessing the extent of organ damage, and identifying abnormal findings that may have contributed to the cause of death. Additionally, virtopsy can aid in forensic investigations, providing valuable evidence in cases of homicide, accidents, and medical malpractice.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Community medicine slides, Topic: Autopsy I.","responses":[{"text":"Virtopsy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ghost autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scan autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monitor autopsy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Necropsy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11775,"text":"A 7-year-old boy decides to put beads in his mouth to blow out on his sister but he accidentally aspirates the beads. One day later, he develops dyspnea, a temperature of 98.4 F, decreased breath sounds and a dull percussion note over the right lobe. Sputum shows normal flora. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"Atelectasis refers to the collapse or closure of a part or the entire lung. **Resorptive atelectasis** occurs when an obstructive lesion, such as a foreign body, blocks a bronchus and prevents the ventilation of the affected lung segment or lobe.\r\n\r\nIn this scenario, the aspiration of beads by the 7-year-old boy has led to the obstruction of a bronchus in the right lobe of the lung. The subsequent lack of ventilation in the affected area causes the alveoli to collapse. This results in decreased breath sounds and a dull percussion note on physical examination.\r\n\r\nThe absence of specific signs of infection, such as an altered sputum with bacteria or inflammatory cells, suggests that the atelectasis is not due to infection, such as bronchiopneumonia or lung abscess. Instead, it is a mechanical obstruction resulting in the collapse of the lung tissue.","reference":"Grott K, Chauhan S, Dunlap JD. Atelectasis. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 20, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545316/","responses":[{"text":"Resorptive atelectasis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiopneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchietelectasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumothorax","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11777,"text":"Which of following will confirm that a parapneumonic effusion has changed into empyema?","explanation":"A **pH value less than 7** is an indicator that a parapneumonic effusion has changed into empyema. Parapneumonic effusion refers to the accumulation of fluid in the pleural space as a result of an underlying pneumonia. In some cases, the effusion may progress to empyema, which is characterized by the presence of purulent material (pus) in the pleural space.\r\n\r\nThe pH of the fluid can help differentiate between a parapneumonic effusion and empyema. A pH below 7 indicates the presence of an acidic environment, which is commonly seen in empyema due to the accumulation of bacteria and the release of inflammatory mediators. A pH value above 7 suggests a more sterile or non-infected fluid, which is typically observed in uncomplicated parapneumonic effusions.\r\n\r\nOther laboratory parameters such as the pleural LDH to serum LDH ratio, pleural glucose to serum glucose ratio, and the presence of a high number of red blood cells (RBCs) can also provide additional diagnostic information. However, the pH value is a reliable indicator for confirming the transformation of a parapneumonic effusion into empyema.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 564.","responses":[{"text":"RBC \u003e1000","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH \u003e 7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural LDH to serum LDH ratio \u003c 0.6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural glucose to serum glucose ratio \u003e 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH \u003c 7","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11780,"text":"Which is the most important side effect of salbutamol that is dose-dependent?","explanation":"**Muscle tremors** are the most important dose-dependent side effect of salbutamol. Salbutamol is a selective beta-2 adrenergic receptor agonist commonly used as a bronchodilator in the treatment of asthma and other respiratory conditions. Activation of beta-2 receptors leads to relaxation of bronchial smooth muscles, resulting in bronchodilation and relief of symptoms.\r\n\r\nHowever, salbutamol can also bind to beta-2 receptors in skeletal muscles, particularly at higher doses. This can lead to the stimulation of skeletal muscle cells and subsequent tremors. Muscle tremors are the most common side effect observed with salbutamol use, especially when administered via inhalation.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that these tremors are generally transient and dose-dependent. They tend to subside as the body adjusts to the medication or when the dosage is reduced. Patients should be educated about this potential side effect to alleviate any concerns and ensure proper adherence to their treatment regimen.","reference":"(1) Nizet TAC. Tremor side effects of salbutamol, quantified by a laser pointer technique. Respiratory Medicine. Published September 1, 2004. Accessed May 10, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0954611104000964 (2) Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 708.","responses":[{"text":"Depression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypertension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muscle tremors","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11785,"text":"A collective dose of radiation to a population can be expressed in which unit?","explanation":"A collective dose of radiation to a population is expressed in the unit called **person-Sievert (person-Sv)**. The person-Sievert is a measure that combines both the quantity and the biological effect of radiation exposure. It takes into account the number of individuals exposed and the average radiation dose received by each individual.\r\n\r\nThe Sievert (Sv) is a unit of equivalent dose that quantifies the biological effect of radiation on human tissues. It takes into consideration the type of radiation and its potential for causing harm. By multiplying the average dose received by each individual in a population by the number of individuals exposed, we obtain the collective dose in person-Sievert.\r\n\r\nThis unit is commonly used in epidemiological studies and risk assessments to evaluate the health effects of radiation exposure on a population. It helps in understanding the overall impact of radiation on a larger scale and aids in making informed decisions regarding radiation safety and protection measures.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Forensic slides, Topic: Nuclear medicine.","responses":[{"text":"Rad","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Becquerel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Person-Sievert","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sievert","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Curie","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11786,"text":"Which of the following is least likely to cause a radiation hazard?","explanation":"Among the options listed, **MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) of the abdomen** is least likely to cause a radiation hazard compared to the other imaging modalities. \r\n\r\nMRI uses a strong magnetic field and radio waves to generate detailed images of the body. Unlike CT scans and X-rays, MRI does not involve the use of ionizing radiation. Instead, it relies on the interaction of magnetic fields with the body's natural alignment of hydrogen atoms. As a result, MRI does not pose a radiation hazard to patients.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, CT scans, X-rays, and fluoroscopic imaging (such as upper GI series and lower GI series) all use ionizing radiation, which carries potential risks related to radiation exposure. The radiation dose and associated hazards vary depending on factors such as the type of examination, the body area being imaged, and the number of exposures.","reference":"Ghadimi M, Sapra A. Magnetic resonance imaging contraindications. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed May 20, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551669/","responses":[{"text":"MRI abdomen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CT head","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper GI series","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray abdomen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower GI series","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11789,"text":"A person commits suicide by slitting his throat, and dies of an air embolism. How did air enter his circulation?","explanation":"The **jugular veins** are major veins that drain deoxygenated blood from the head and neck and return it to the heart. When the throat is slit, the integrity of the neck structures, including the veins, is compromised, allowing air to enter the vasculature.\r\n\r\nThe entry of air into the jugular vein can occur due to the negative pressure created during inspiration. If the person takes a breath after slitting their throat, air can be drawn into the veins through the open wound. This air can then travel through the venous system and potentially reach the heart and other organs, causing an air embolism.\r\n\r\nAn air embolism occurs when air bubbles obstruct blood flow, leading to impaired circulation and tissue damage. In the case of a jugular vein air embolism, the air bubbles can be carried to the heart and then dispersed throughout the body, affecting various organs and tissues.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 301.","responses":[{"text":"External carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jugular vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vertrebral artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11790,"text":"Which of the following is released by macrophages to activate Th1?","explanation":"Macrophages play a crucial role in activating the Th1 immune response by releasing specific cytokines. One of the key cytokines released by macrophages to activate Th1 cells is **interleukin-12 (IL-12)**. IL-12 acts as a bridge between the innate and adaptive immune responses by promoting the differentiation of naive T cells into Th1 cells.\r\n\r\nUpon encountering antigens, macrophages phagocytose and process them, leading to the presentation of antigenic peptides on their cell surface. This activates the macrophages to secrete IL-12. IL-12, in turn, binds to its receptor on naive T cells, promoting their differentiation into Th1 cells. Th1 cells are responsible for initiating cell-mediated immune responses and activating cytotoxic T cells, which are important in clearing intracellular pathogens.\r\n\r\nIL-12 also enhances the production of interferon-gamma (IFN-gamma) by Th1 cells, further amplifying the Th1 response. IFN-gamma plays a critical role in activating macrophages to enhance their phagocytic and bactericidal functions.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 372.","responses":[{"text":"TNF-gamma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IL-8","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12508,"text":"Caplan syndrome consists of which of the following two features?","explanation":"**Caplan syndrome** consists of the features of **rheumatoid arthritis** and **pneumoconiosis**. It is characterized by the presence of rheumatoid arthritis in individuals who have been exposed to certain types of occupational dust, such as coal dust or silica dust. \r\n\r\n**Pneumoconiosis** refers to the lung disease caused by the inhalation of mineral or inorganic dust particles, which can result in lung fibrosis and nodular opacities. In Caplan syndrome, these nodules are seen in conjunction with the joint inflammation and deformities of rheumatoid arthritis.","reference":"Nemakayala DR, Surmachevska N, Ramphul K. Caplan syndrome. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 16, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499886/","responses":[{"text":"Asbestosis and tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatoid arthritis and systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestosis and rheumatoid arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumoconiosis and rheumatoid arthritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestosis and lung carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12509,"text":"A 65-year-old female patient, who suffered from cerebral infarction 3 weeks ago, recovered and started walking. She suddenly started getting tachypneic and died within 30 minutes with failed attempts of resuscitation. Autopsy finding revealed saddle embolus in the pulmonary artery. Which of the following caused the death of the patient?","explanation":"**Electromechanical dissociation (EMD)** refers to a situation where there is a lack of effective mechanical contraction of the heart despite the presence of electrical activity. It is a form of cardiac arrest characterized by the absence of a palpable pulse despite the presence of electrical activity on an electrocardiogram (ECG). In this case, the saddle embolus in the pulmonary artery has obstructed blood flow to the lungs, leading to acute pulmonary embolism. The resulting increase in pulmonary vascular resistance and right ventricular strain can cause acute right-sided heart failure and subsequent electromechanical dissociation.\r\n\r\nThe patient's sudden onset of tachypnea and subsequent death within 30 minutes, despite failed attempts at resuscitation, are consistent with the rapid and severe consequences of a large **saddle embolus**. The obstruction of blood flow to the lungs leads to a significant decrease in oxygenation and impaired cardiac function, ultimately resulting in electromechanical dissociation and subsequent death.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 39.","responses":[{"text":"Interstitial fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemorrhagic infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electromechanical dissociation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute cor pulmonale","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12510,"text":"A healthy male jogger fell down while running and suddenly developed difficulty in breathing. On clinical examination, his left lung was hyper-resonant and air rushed out when a tube was placed in the right lung. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis in this case is pneumothorax. **Pneumothorax** refers to the presence of air in the pleural space, which can lead to lung collapse. The sudden onset of **difficulty in breathing, hyper-resonance on percussion**, and **air rushing out when a tube is placed** in the lung are characteristic findings of pneumothorax. \r\n\r\nIt commonly occurs due to lung trauma or rupture of a small subpleural bleb, as can happen during activities such as running or vigorous exercise. Prompt medical intervention is necessary to relieve the pneumothorax and re-expand the lung.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 722. (2) Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 178.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrothorax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumothorax","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12511,"text":"What type of hypersensitivity is seen in asthma?","explanation":"The type of hypersensitivity seen in asthma is **type I hypersensitivity**. Type I hypersensitivity, also known as immediate hypersensitivity or allergic hypersensitivity, is characterized by the involvement of IgE antibodies and the release of histamine and other mediators from mast cells and basophils. \r\n\r\nIn **asthma**, exposure to specific allergens leads to an exaggerated immune response, triggering the release of inflammatory mediators that cause bronchoconstriction, airway inflammation, and increased mucus production, resulting in the characteristic symptoms of asthma.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"Type I","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Type IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12512,"text":"Atopic asthma most commonly manifests at what age?","explanation":"**Atopic asthma** most commonly manifests during childhood. It often starts in **early childhood**, although it can develop at any age. Atopy refers to a **genetic predisposition to develop allergic diseases**, and individuals with a family history of allergies or atopic conditions are more likely to develop atopic asthma. The symptoms of atopic asthma are typically triggered by exposure to allergens such as pollen, dust mites, pet dander, or certain foods.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"Neonatal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Childhood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Adulthood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Teenage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Old age","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12513,"text":"A man, who is a miner by occupation, is exposed to dust particles. Which particle deposits in the lower lobes of the lungs?","explanation":"**Asbestos particles** are known to deposit in the lower lobes of the lungs. Asbestos is a mineral fiber commonly found in certain industries such as mining, construction, and insulation. Prolonged exposure to asbestos can lead to the development of various respiratory diseases, including asbestosis, lung cancer, and mesothelioma. The deposition of asbestos fibers in the lower lobes of the lungs is characteristic of asbestos-related diseases.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 689-691.","responses":[{"text":"Carbon dust","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beryllium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestos","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silica","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12514,"text":"A pneumonia patient has a CURB-65 score of 4.0. How will you manage the patient?","explanation":"A **CURB-65** score of 4.0 indicates a severe pneumonia requiring hospitalization and close monitoring. The CURB-65 scoring system is used to assess the severity of community-acquired pneumonia and helps guide the appropriate level of care.\r\n\r\nIn this case, with a CURB-65 score of 4.0, the recommended management is admission to the hospital and administration of antibiotics. The patient may require treatment in an **intensive care unit (ICU)** or **high-dependency unit (HDU)** due to the severity of the pneumonia.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 583.","responses":[{"text":"Admit in ward and administer antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No treatment needed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hospital-supervised outpatient treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Home treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intensive care unit (ICU) and high-dependency unit (HDU) for severe pneumonia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12754,"text":"Which of the following increases in obstructive pulmonary diseases?","explanation":"**Obstructive pulmonary diseases**, such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, and bronchiectasis, are characterized by airflow limitation and difficulty in exhaling air from the lungs. **Residual volume (RV)** refers to the volume of air that remains in the lungs after maximal exhalation. In obstructive diseases, there is an **increase in air trapping**, causing the RV to be elevated.\r\n\r\nTidal volume (TV) represents the volume of air inhaled or exhaled during normal breathing and is not necessarily increased in obstructive pulmonary diseases.\r\n\r\nVital capacity (VC) is the maximum volume of air that can be exhaled forcefully after a maximal inhalation. In obstructive diseases, the VC may be reduced due to increased airway resistance.\r\n\r\nForced expiratory volume (FEV) measures the volume of air forcefully exhaled during specific time intervals, such as FEV1 (forced expiratory volume in 1 second). FEV1 is decreased in obstructive diseases.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 554.","responses":[{"text":"Forced expiratory volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tidal volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vital capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Residual volume","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12755,"text":"What is the treatment for hypersensitivity pneumonitis?","explanation":"**Hypersensitivity pneumonitis**, also known as extrinsic allergic alveolitis, is an inflammatory lung disease caused by an immune response to the inhalation of certain antigens. These antigens can be organic substances such as mold, bacteria, or animal proteins, typically found in occupational or environmental settings.\r\n\r\nThe primary treatment approach for hypersensitivity pneumonitis is twofold: glucocorticoids and removal of antigen exposure.\r\n\r\n**Glucocorticoids**, such as prednisone, are used to reduce inflammation and suppress the immune response. They help alleviate symptoms and prevent further lung damage. The dosage and duration of glucocorticoid therapy depend on the severity of the disease.\r\n\r\nIn addition to medication, it is crucial to identify and **remove the source of antigen exposure** to prevent further episodes of hypersensitivity pneumonitis. This may involve changes in occupational or environmental settings, such as avoiding the allergen or using protective equipment.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 617.","responses":[{"text":"Antibiotics and removal of antigen exposure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucocorticoids and removal of antigen exposure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchodilators","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucocorticoids and bronchodilators","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No treatment needed","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12756,"text":"A 6-year-old child presented to the clinic with lethargy, drooling, and high grade fever. On examination, he has epiglottitis. What is the most common causative agent of his condition?","explanation":"The most common causative agent of epiglottitis in children is **Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib)**. **Epiglottitis** is an acute inflammatory condition characterized by inflammation and swelling of the epiglottis, which can cause airway obstruction and respiratory distress. Hib is a **gram-negative bacterium that colonizes the respiratory tract and can cause severe invasive infections such as epiglottitis, meningitis, and pneumonia.\r\n\r\nSince the introduction of the Hib vaccine as part of routine childhood immunization programs, the incidence of Hib-related epiglottitis has significantly decreased. However, in unvaccinated or incompletely vaccinated individuals, Hib infection remains a concern. \r\n\r\nOther less common causes of epiglottitis include Streptococcus pneumoniae, Staphylococcus aureus, and rarely, viral or fungal infections.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 165.","responses":[{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudomonas aeruginosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilus influenzae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Actinobacteria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12757,"text":"Rain is usually slightly acidic with a pH of 5.6 due to the presence of carbon dioxide. In acidic rain, a pH of 4.6 is found due to the presence of which of the following two components?","explanation":"The presence of **sulfur and nitrogen** compounds contributes to the acidity of the rain. **Acidic rain** is formed when pollutants, primarily sulfur dioxide (SO2) and nitrogen oxides (NOx), are released into the atmosphere through industrial processes, fossil fuel combustion, and transportation. These pollutants react with water, oxygen, and other atmospheric components to form sulfuric acid (H2SO4) and nitric acid (HNO3), respectively. When rainwater contains elevated levels of these acids, it becomes more acidic, resulting in a lower pH value. The combination of sulfur and nitrogen compounds in the atmosphere is responsible for the increased acidity in rain.","reference":"US EPA O. What is acid rain? Published February 9, 2016. Accessed November 27, 2022. https://www.epa.gov/acidrain/what-acid-rain","responses":[{"text":"Sulphur and carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrogen and hydrocarbons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphur and nitrogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrogen and carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulfur and hydrocarbons","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12758,"text":"What is the treatment for croup?","explanation":"The treatment for **croup**, which is a viral infection that causes inflammation and narrowing of the upper airways, typically involves supportive care and medications to alleviate symptoms. The primary treatment options for croup include:\r\n\r\nHumidified air or cool mist: This can help soothe the inflamed airways and relieve coughing.\r\nCorticosteroids: **Oral dexamethasone** is commonly used and has been shown to reduce airway inflammation and improve symptoms. It is often given as a single dose.\r\nNebulized epinephrine: Racemic epinephrine is a bronchodilator that helps reduce airway swelling and improve breathing. It is typically used in more severe cases of croup or when symptoms are not responding to other treatments.\r\n\r\nAntiviral therapy is not routinely used for the treatment of croup, as the condition is primarily caused by viral infections. Acyclovir is an antiviral medication primarily used for the treatment of herpes virus infections and is not effective against the viruses that cause croup.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 628.","responses":[{"text":"Acyclovir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Racemic epinephrine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral dexamethasone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Antiviral therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous corticosteroids","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12759,"text":"Which of the following gases is found in the upper part of the atmosphere and absorbs ultraviolet rays but is dangerous when found near the surface?","explanation":"The gas found in the upper part of the atmosphere that absorbs ultraviolet rays is **ozone (O₃)**. Ozone is formed naturally in the stratosphere and plays a crucial role in protecting the Earth from harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation. It acts as a shield, absorbing most of the UV-B and UV-C rays from the sun.\r\n\r\nHowever, ozone near the Earth's surface, in the lower atmosphere or troposphere, can be harmful. It is a primary component of smog and air pollution.\r\n\r\nHigh concentrations of ground-level ozone are formed by the reaction of sunlight with pollutants such as nitrogen oxides (NOₓ) and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) emitted by vehicles, industrial processes, and other sources. \r\n\r\nExposure to high levels of ground-level ozone can cause respiratory problems, eye irritation, and other health issues, particularly for vulnerable individuals such as those with respiratory conditions or the elderly.\r\n\r\nCarbon dioxide (CO₂) is a greenhouse gas that contributes to climate change but does not directly absorb ultraviolet rays. Oxygen (O₂), nitrogen dioxide (NO₂), and nitrate (NO₃) do not absorb ultraviolet rays to the extent that ozone does and are not primarily associated with the absorption of UV radiation.","reference":"US EPA O. What is Ozone? Published March 21, 2016. Accessed November 27, 2022. https://www.epa.gov/ozone-pollution-and-your-patients-health/what-ozone","responses":[{"text":"O₂","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NO₃","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CO₂","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"NO₂","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"O₃","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12760,"text":"Which of the following defines the term 'half-life' of a radioactive isotope?","explanation":"The **half-life** of a **radioactive isotope** is the time it takes for half of the radioactive atoms in a sample to undergo **radioactive decay**. It is a characteristic property of each radioactive isotope and is constant for that specific isotope. During each half-life, the amount of radioactive material decreases by half, while the remaining half remains in the sample. This process continues exponentially over subsequent half-lives.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory-II module, Community Medicine slides: Nuclear Medicine.","responses":[{"text":"The time taken for the radioactive activity of the isotope to decrease by half","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The time taken by the entire isotopic mass to decay","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Half of the time taken by the radioactive isotope to decay","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The time taken by half the mass of the isotope to decay","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12761,"text":"Gamma Knife is classified under which of the following medical techniques?","explanation":"**Gamma Knife** is classified under the category of **radiological surgery**. The Gamma Knife is a non-invasive surgical technique used for the treatment of various brain disorders, including tumors, arteriovenous malformations (AVMs), and functional disorders like trigeminal neuralgia. \r\n\r\nIt is a form of **stereotactic radiosurgery** that utilizes **gamma radiation** to precisely target and treat specific areas of the brain. The technique involves the use of multiple converging beams of gamma rays that intersect at a specific point within the brain, delivering a high dose of radiation to the targeted area while minimizing radiation exposure to surrounding healthy tissues.","reference":"Gamma knife. Ont Health Technol Assess Ser. 2002;2(2):1-22. Accessed June 21, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3387771/","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prophylactic medicine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nuclear medicine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiological surgery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diagnostic method","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12762,"text":"Which field in medicine comprises of the practice of using radioactive isotopes which give off small amounts of radiation?","explanation":"**Radiology** is a medical specialty that involves the use of various imaging techniques to diagnose and treat diseases and conditions. One of the subspecialties within radiology is **nuclear medicine**, which utilizes **radioactive isotopes** to create images and perform certain therapeutic procedures. \r\n\r\nIn nuclear medicine, small amounts of radioactive materials, known as radiopharmaceuticals or radiotracers, are administered to patients. These radiopharmaceuticals emit gamma rays, which can be detected by specialized imaging devices, such as gamma cameras or positron emission tomography (PET) scanners. By analyzing the patterns of radiation emitted by the radiopharmaceuticals, radiologists can obtain information about the structure and function of organs and tissues in the body, aiding in the diagnosis and management of various diseases.","reference":"Definition of radiology. Accessed November 27, 2022. https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/radiology","responses":[{"text":"Neurology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immunology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ophthalmology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephrology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiology","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12763,"text":"Nuclear medicine comes under which of the following fields?","explanation":"Nuclear medicine comes under the field of **radiology**. **Nuclear medicine** is a medical specialty that uses radioactive substances and imaging techniques to diagnose and treat various conditions. It involves the use of small amounts of radioactive materials, called radiotracers or radiopharmaceuticals, which are administered to patients either orally, intravenously, or by inhalation. These **radiotracers** emit gamma rays that are detected by special cameras, known as gamma cameras, or other imaging devices. The images produced by nuclear medicine techniques provide information about the functioning and structure of organs and tissues within the body.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory-II module, Community Medicine slides: Nuclear Medicine.","responses":[{"text":"Radiology","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otolaryngology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pediatrics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematology","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12764,"text":"Which of the following refers to the study of man and machinery in a workplace?","explanation":"**Ergonomics** is the study of how humans interact with their work environment, including the design of equipment, tasks, and workspaces to optimize safety, efficiency, and well-being. It focuses on creating a harmonious relationship between humans and machines in the workplace to enhance productivity and prevent injuries or discomfort associated with work-related activities.\r\n\r\nCommunity medicine, also known as preventive medicine or public health, is a field that focuses on the health of populations and communities.\r\n\r\nBioscience is a broad term that encompasses various scientific disciplines related to the study of living organisms. It includes fields such as biology, biochemistry, genetics, and biotechnology.\r\n\r\nBiotechnology refers to the use of biological systems, organisms, or their components to develop or create products and technologies for various applications.\r\n\r\nEnvironmental study, or environmental science, is an interdisciplinary field that examines the interactions between humans and the environment.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory-II slides, Community Medicine slides: Occupational Health.","responses":[{"text":"Environmental study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Community medicine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Biotechnology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ergonomics","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bioscience","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12765,"text":"What is the management of epiglottitis in children?","explanation":"The management of epiglottitis in children involves **securing the airway** as the top priority. **Epiglottitis** is a potentially life-threatening condition characterized by inflammation and swelling of the epiglottis, which can lead to **airway obstruction**. Therefore, ensuring a patent airway is crucial. This is typically done by endotracheal intubation or, in some cases, by establishing a surgical airway (tracheostomy). \r\n\r\nOnce the airway is secured, intravenous antibiotics are administered to treat the underlying infection. The specific choice of antibiotics depends on local antimicrobial susceptibility patterns and may include third-generation cephalosporins or other appropriate broad-spectrum antibiotics. \r\n\r\nAntiviral therapy, bronchodilators, and examining the throat with a tongue depressor are not part of the primary management of epiglottitis.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory-II module, Pediatrics slides: Upper airway infection management in children.","responses":[{"text":"Antiviral therapy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secure the airway","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchodilators","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intravenous antibiotics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Examine the throat with a tongue depressor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12771,"text":"What is the ideal situation for a dead body to be stored in the mortuary?","explanation":"The ideal situation for a dead body to be stored in the mortuary is when **the body is refrigerated but not frozen**. **Refrigeration** slows down the decomposition process and helps preserve the body until it can be prepared for burial, cremation, or other disposition methods. The recommended temperature for mortuary refrigeration is typically between **2-4 degrees Celsius (36-39 degrees Fahrenheit)**. This temperature range helps inhibit bacterial growth and decomposition while minimizing the risk of tissue damage that can occur with freezing.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 100.","responses":[{"text":"Temperature below freezing point","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"After mummification of the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Body is refrigerated but not frozen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Submerged in salt solution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Buried in soil","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12772,"text":"Which incision is done on the scalp while preserving the facial features?","explanation":"The autopsy incision that is done on the scalp while preserving the facial features is the **mastoid incision**. This incision is made behind the ear, extending downward towards the nec and allows access to the base of the skull and the brain without significantly altering the appearance of the face. It is commonly used in forensic autopsies to examine the skull and its contents while **minimizing visible changes to the facial features**.\r\n\r\n\r\n The Y-shaped incision is a common method used in autopsies to open the chest and abdomen and involves making a vertical incision from the middle of the chest down to the pubic bone, and two additional horizontal incisions across the chest and abdomen, forming a Y shape. It allows access to the major organs for examination.\r\n\r\nThe V-shaped incision is a method used in autopsies to open the chest and abdomen and involves making a vertical incision in the midline of the chest and abdomen, which then splits into two angled incisions extending outward, resembling the shape of a V. It allows for easy access to the thoracic and abdominal organs for examination.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 108.","responses":[{"text":"Y-shaped incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mastoid incision","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"V-shaped incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subdural incision","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calvarine incision","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12774,"text":"A body is received from a crime scene in which the death is suspected to be from strangulation of the neck. What type of incision should be made in this case?","explanation":"In cases where the cause of death is suspected to be strangulation of the neck, a **modified Y-shaped incision** is typically made during the autopsy.\r\n\r\nThe modified Y-shaped incision involves making a **midline incision** from the **suprasternal notch** down to the **pubic symphysis**, and then extending transversely across the chest at the level of the nipples. From the ends of the transverse incision, two diagonal incisions are made, extending laterally and superiorly towards the shoulders. This results in an incision pattern that resembles a Y shape.\r\n\r\nThe purpose of the modified Y-shaped incision is to provide adequate exposure to the neck structures, including the underlying soft tissues, blood vessels, and structures such as the hyoid bone, thyroid cartilage, and trachea. It allows for thorough examination and documentation of any injuries or findings related to the suspected strangulation.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 103.","responses":[{"text":"V-shaped","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified Y-shaped","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Y-shaped","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"I-shaped","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified I-shaped","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12777,"text":"A body was found with a horizontal mark on the neck and ecchymosis around it. It is a case of strangulation which is different from hanging. How is strangulation different from hanging?","explanation":"In cases of strangulation, the **ligature mark** is usually **more horizontal** compared to hanging. This is because in strangulation, external force is applied horizontally around the neck, often with a hand or a ligature, resulting in a mark that encircles the neck in a more horizontal direction.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, in hanging, the ligature mark is typically higher on the neck and is more oblique or diagonal. This is because in hanging, the weight of the body applies force vertically, causing the ligature mark to be higher and at an angle.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 168.","responses":[{"text":"Multiple ligature marks are seen in strangulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No ecchymosis is present in hanging","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ligature mark in strangulation is more horizontal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hanging causes a deeper ligature mark","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12779,"text":"A body was found drowned in a stream. Where will hypostasis be seen in the body?","explanation":"**Postmortem staining or lividity** is a bluish or purplish-red discoloration caused by blood settling in the capillaries and venules of the dependent parts of the deceased body. The staining occurs due to gravity and varies based on the body's position. \r\n\r\nIn cases of drowning, where the body remains submerged in water, the head, being the heaviest, settles at a lower level compared to the rest of the body. Consequently, staining is typically observed on the face, upper chest, hands, lower arms, feet, and calves, which are the dependent areas. \r\n\r\nHowever, if the body is in **flowing water** (e.g., stream) and constantly changing positions, **staining may not occur**.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 144.","responses":[{"text":"Back of the body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No lividity will be seen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Front of face and neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Back of face and neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dependent part of upper limbs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12781,"text":"What type of autopsy is performed in the dead body of a drug addict or HIV patient?","explanation":"In the case of a deceased drug addict or HIV patient, the type of autopsy that is typically performed is the **Rokitansky method**.\r\n\r\nThe Rokitansky method is a technique in which organs are dissected in their original location without major removal from the body. This method, while not commonly employed, can be beneficial for cases involving patients with contagious diseases, as it minimizes the risk of spreading infection during the autopsy procedure.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 103.","responses":[{"text":"Ghon method","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Letulle method","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rokitansky method","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Virchow's method","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"En bloc removal method","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12782,"text":"A person found guilty is sentenced to death by hanging. What is the cause of death in judicial hanging?","explanation":"The cause of death in judicial hanging is typically attributed to **neck fracture**, specifically fracture of the second cervical vertebra (C2), also known as the axis.\r\n\r\nDuring hanging, when the person is suspended with a noose around the neck, the weight of the body creates tension on the neck structures. The force and pressure applied to the neck can result in several mechanisms of injury, including fracture of the C2 vertebra, also known as the hangman's fracture. This fracture involves the neural arch of C2 and can cause spinal cord injury.\r\n\r\nThe neural arch fracture can lead to disruption of the spinal cord and associated neural structures, resulting in rapid loss of neurological function and ultimately causing death.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 167.","responses":[{"text":"Asphyxia by neck compression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Choking","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skull fracture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Strangulation of neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neck fracture of the 2nd cervical vertebra","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12783,"text":"A person died from drowning. His lungs were clogged and froth was found coming out of his mouth and nose. What type of artifact is this?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 400.","responses":[{"text":"Prinsloo Gordon artifact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Artifact due to postmortem changes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Therapeutic artifact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heat artifact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Agonal artifact","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13740,"text":"In an arterial blood gas (ABG) test, pH = 7.38, pO2 = 30 mmHg, and pCO2 = 50 mmHg. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"Based on the provided arterial blood gas (ABG) values, the most likely diagnosis is **type 2 respiratory failure**.\r\n\r\nType 2 respiratory failure, also known as **hypercapnic respiratory failure**, is characterized by **elevated levels of arterial carbon dioxide (pCO2)**. In this case, the pCO2 value of 50 mmHg indicates inadequate ventilation and an accumulation of carbon dioxide in the blood.\r\n\r\nThe pH value of 7.38 falls within the normal range (7.35-7.45) and does not suggest an acid-base imbalance.\r\n\r\nRespiratory alkalosis is characterized by a high pH and low pCO2, which is not present in this case.\r\n\r\nRespiratory acidosis is characterized by low pH and high pCO2, which is not seen here.\r\n\r\nType 1 respiratory failure, or hypoxemic respiratory failure, is characterized by low levels of arterial oxygen (pO2). However, in this case, the pO2 value of 30 mmHg suggests inadequate oxygenation of the blood, but the primary issue lies with elevated carbon dioxide levels (Type 2 respiratory failure)","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 565.","responses":[{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 respiratory failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 2 respiratory failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13741,"text":"In an arterial blood gas (ABG) test, pH = 7.32, pO2 = 30 mmHg, and pCO2 = 25 mmHg. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Type 1 respiratory failure**, also known as hypoxemic respiratory failure, is characterized by **low levels of arterial oxygen (pO2)** along with normal or low levels of arterial carbon dioxide (pCO2). In this case, the low pO2 value of 30 mmHg indicates inadequate oxygenation of the blood.\r\n\r\nRespiratory acidosis is characterized by low pH and high pCO2, which is not present in this case.\r\n\r\nRespiratory alkalosis is characterized by a high pH and low pCO2, which is also not seen here.\r\n\r\nType 2 respiratory failure, also known as hypercapnic respiratory failure, is characterized by elevated levels of arterial carbon dioxide (pCO2). However, in this case, the pCO2 value of 25 mmHg is normal or slightly lower than normal, suggesting adequate ventilation and not indicating Type 2 respiratory failure.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 565.","responses":[{"text":"Type 1 respiratory failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 2 respiratory failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13742,"text":"A young woman was being treated with antibiotics for postpartum sepsis since 2 days. She suddenly developed tachypnea and cyanosis. What will be found on lung biopsy?","explanation":"This young woman who developed tachypnea and cyanosis while being treated for postpartum sepsis most likely has **acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS)**, histologically characterized **hyaline membrane in the alveoli**.\r\n\r\nThese clinical features and the history of sepsis following childbirth are suggestive of ARDS. ARDS is a severe form of respiratory failure characterized by the rapid onset of widespread inflammation in the lungs, leading to increased permeability of the alveolar-capillary membrane and subsequent accumulation of protein-rich fluid in the alveoli.\r\n\r\nThe presence of hyaline membrane in the alveoli is a characteristic histopathological finding in ARDS. Hyaline membranes are formed by the accumulation of proteinaceous material, fibrin, and cellular debris lining the alveolar walls. They contribute to the impairment of gas exchange and are associated with the severe respiratory compromise seen in ARDS.\r\n\r\nOther histopathological findings, such as fibrosis and scarring, neutrophil infiltrate, respiratory bronchiole damage, or lymphocyte infiltrate, are not typically seen in the early stages of ARDS but may be observed in later stages or in specific conditions associated with distinct histopathological patterns.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 94.","responses":[{"text":"Hyaline membrane in alveoli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory bronchiole damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophil infiltrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrosis and scarring","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocyte infiltrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13745,"text":"A 45-year-old male smoker has a dry cough. On physical examination, he has crackles and clubbing. The radiograph shows honeycomb cysts and traction bronchiectasis. What type of interstitial pneumonia does the man most likely have?","explanation":"The most likely type of interstitial pneumonia the man has based on the clincal presentation is **desquamative interstitial pneumonia**. This is suggested by the combination of clinical findings, including a dry cough, crackles, and clubbing, along with radiographic features such as **honeycomb cysts** and **traction bronchiectasis**. Desquamative interstitial pneumonia is a form of interstitial lung disease that is strongly associated with **smoking** and most commonly affects men between 40-60 years.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 605, 606.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytic interstitial pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Usual interstitial pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Desquamative interstitial pneumonia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute interstitial pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Non-specific interstitial pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15946,"text":"What part of the manuscript is the last to be finalized?","explanation":"The **title** of a manuscript is typically finalized at the end of the writing process, after all the other sections such as the abstract, introduction, methods, results, and discussion have been completed. The title is usually revised and refined to accurately reflect the content and focus of the study and to attract the attention of readers. It is important to finalize the title last to ensure that it effectively captures the essence of the research and aligns with the findings and conclusions presented in the manuscript.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Community-medicine slides, Topic: Medical writing.","responses":[{"text":"Title","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Discussion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Objective","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methods","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Results","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15948,"text":"Exposure to air pollution increases the risk of which of the following diseases?","explanation":"Exposure to **air pollution** has been associated with an increased risk of several diseases, including **chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and asthma**. Air pollution, particularly fine particulate matter (PM2.5) and certain gaseous pollutants, can irritate the airways and lead to inflammation and narrowing of the bronchial tubes. This can exacerbate existing respiratory conditions such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and asthma. Prolonged exposure to air pollution can also contribute to the development of these conditions in individuals who are susceptible.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Community-medicine slides, Topic: Air pollution.","responses":[{"text":"Leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac diseases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"COPD and asthma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15949,"text":"Which of the following is the cause of cat-scratch disease?","explanation":"**Cat-scratch disease (CSD)** is an infectious disease caused by the bacterium ***Bartonella henselae***. It is primarily transmitted to humans through scratches or bites from infected cats, although fleas associated with the cats can also serve as vectors for the bacteria. CSD is most commonly seen in children and young adults who have close contact with cats.\r\n\r\nThe course of cat-scratch disease typically starts with a small papule or pustule at the site of the scratch or bite, which may develop into a red, swollen lesion known as an inoculation site or primary lesion. Lymph nodes near the scratch or bite site then become enlarged and tender, leading to regional lymphadenopathy. This is often the most characteristic feature of the disease.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 170.","responses":[{"text":"Mycobacterium leprae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unknown etiology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram-negative bacilli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Treponema pallidum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15950,"text":"What is a type I or alpha error in hypothesis testing?","explanation":"A **type I error**, also known as an **alpha error**, occurs in hypothesis testing when the null hypothesis is actually true, but it is incorrectly rejected. In other words, a type I error is the incorrect rejection of a true null hypothesis. It is represented by rejecting the null hypothesis when it should have been accepted.","reference":"Dow lecture slides: Respiratory module, Community-medicine slides, Topic: The objective, title, and hypothesis writing.","responses":[{"text":"The null hypothesis is false and rejected","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The null hypothesis is false and not rejected","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The null hypothesis is true and rejected","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The null hypothesis is true and accepted","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The null hypothesis is true and not rejected","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15952,"text":"Which of the following is characterized by repeated bouts of binge eating along with a desire to lose weight?","explanation":"The condition characterized by repeated bouts of binge eating along with a desire to lose weight is called bulimia nervosa. **Bulimia nervosa** is an eating disorder where individuals engage in episodes of **excessive food consumption (binge eating)** followed by **compensatory behaviors** such as self-induced vomiting, excessive exercise, or the use of laxatives or diuretics to prevent weight gain. It is often accompanied by a distorted body image and an intense fear of gaining weight. Unlike in anorexia nervosa, individuals with bulimia nervosa typically maintain a **relatively normal body weight**.","reference":"Jain A, Yilanli M. Bulimia nervosa. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed May 25, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562178/","responses":[{"text":"Binge eating","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obesity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anorexia nervosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bulimia nervosa","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16075,"text":"Which of the following is an example of medical writing that comprises academic writing for marketing purposes?","explanation":"**Health magazines** can be considered as an example of medical writing that comprises academic writing for **marketing purposes**.\r\n\r\nHealth magazines are publications that target a general audience and provide information on various health topics, including medical conditions, treatments, lifestyle choices, and wellness. While they may contain some scientific information, their primary purpose is to educate and engage readers rather than present in-depth research findings.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory module, Community-medicine slides, Topic: Medical writing.","responses":[{"text":"Research article","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Health magazines","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Books","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Journal article","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16076,"text":"Which gas is known as sewer gas?","explanation":"The gas known as **sewer gas** is hydrogen sulfide (H2S). **Hydrogen sulfide** is a colorless gas with a characteristic rotten egg odor. It is commonly found in sewage systems, septic tanks, and areas with decomposing organic matter. Exposure to high concentrations of hydrogen sulfide can be hazardous to human health, as it is toxic and can cause various symptoms such as respiratory irritation, headache, dizziness, and in extreme cases, it can be lethal.","reference":"Hydrogen sulfide | niosh | cdc. Published April 18, 2022. Accessed June 7, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/topics/hydrogensulfide/default.html","responses":[{"text":"Methane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon monoxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrogen sulphide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Ozone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphur dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16077,"text":"Which greenhouse gas contributes the most to global warming?","explanation":"**Carbon dioxide (CO2)** is the greenhouse gas that contributes the most to global warming. While other gases like methane (CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O), and ozone (O3) also have warming effects, carbon dioxide is the primary **greenhouse gas** responsible for the long-term increase in Earth's average temperature. Carbon dioxide is released through various human activities such as burning fossil fuels (coal, oil, and natural gas), deforestation, and industrial processes. Its high concentration and long atmospheric lifetime make it a significant contributor to the greenhouse effect and climate change.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Respiratory module, Community-medicine slides, Topic: Air pollution.","responses":[{"text":"Ozone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon dioxide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Methane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon monoxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16128,"text":"Acid-fast bacilli in macrophages and noncaseating granulomas are seen in which of the following conditions?","explanation":"The presence of **acid-fast bacilli in macrophages** and **noncaseating granulomas** is seen in *Mycobacterium leprae* infection.\r\n\r\n***Mycobacterium leprae*** is the causative organism of leprosy, also known as Hansen's disease. Leprosy is a chronic infectious disease that primarily affects the skin and peripheral nerves.\r\n\r\nThe characteristic histopathological finding in leprosy is the presence of noncaseating granulomas. These granulomas consist of a collection of macrophages, lymphocytes, and multinucleated giant cells. Acid-fast bacilli can be detected within macrophages or histiocytes, indicating the presence of the mycobacterial infection.\r\n\r\nOther conditions, such as sarcoidosis and cat-scratch disease, may involve granuloma formation but do not typically exhibit acid-fast bacilli.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 101.","responses":[{"text":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cat-scratch disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium leprae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16130,"text":"A man, working in a sandblasting factory, develops shortness of breath, and a non-productive cough. His pulmonary function tests show a restrictive pattern. He takes no respiratory precautions in his workplace. Which of the following diseases has he most likely developed?","explanation":"This man's history of working in a **sandblasting factory** and the development of shortness of breath and a non-productive cough is most consistent with **silicosis**. Silicosis is a lung disease caused by the inhalation of crystalline silica dust, which is commonly found in industries such as sandblasting, mining, and construction. Prolonged exposure to silica dust leads to the formation of fibrous nodules in the lungs, causing inflammation and scarring, and resulting in a restrictive pattern on pulmonary function tests. Symptoms of silicosis include shortness of breath, cough, fatigue, and chest pain. It is important for individuals working in occupations with potential silica exposure to take proper respiratory precautions to minimize the risk of developing silicosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 415.","responses":[{"text":"Asbestosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Berylliosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silicosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anthracosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bagassosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16131,"text":"A 36-year-old female, a mother of three children, comes to the emergency department with shortness of breath that started a few hours ago. She has a history of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) and is on oral contraceptives for 1 year. With this history, what will be the best investigation choice?","explanation":"Given the patient's history of **deep vein thrombosis (DVT)** and the acute onset of shortness of breath, the most appropriate investigation choice would be **computed tomography (CT) pulmonary angiography**. CT pulmonary angiography is a commonly used imaging technique to diagnose **pulmonary embolism (PE)**, which occurs when a blood clot (usually from a DVT) travels to the pulmonary arteries and blocks blood flow to the lungs. CT pulmonary angiography allows visualization of the pulmonary vasculature and can help identify the presence and location of a pulmonary embolism. This test is considered the gold standard for diagnosing PE and is commonly used in the evaluation of patients with suspected pulmonary embolism.","reference":"1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 700-703.\r\n\r\n2)  Klok FA, Mos ICM, Kroft LJM, de Roos A, Huisman MV. Computed tomography pulmonary angiography as a single imaging test to rule out pulmonary embolism. Current Opinion in Pulmonary Medicine. Published September 2011. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21681098/","responses":[{"text":"Computed tomography (CT) pulmonary angiography","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echocardiography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnetic resonance imaging","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16134,"text":"Which of the following is mandatory for doing any kind of autopsy?","explanation":"The requirement for doing any kind of autopsy can vary depending on the jurisdiction and specific circumstances. However, in general, **authorization or consent** is typically required to perform an autopsy. This authorization can come from different sources, such as the legal next of kin, a designated representative, a medical examiner, or a court order. The specific requirements may differ based on local laws, regulations, and cultural practices. Therefore, it is important to consult the applicable legal and ethical guidelines in a particular jurisdiction to determine the necessary authorization for conducting an autopsy.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 99-100.","responses":[{"text":"Authorization","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magistrate inquest","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adequate daylight","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Consent of relative","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16157,"text":"In what case is a psychological autopsy performed?","explanation":"A **psychological autopsy** is typically performed in cases of **suicide**. It is a comprehensive investigation conducted to understand the psychological factors and circumstances leading to a person's suicide. This involves gathering information about the individual's mental state, behavioral patterns, social relationships, and other relevant factors through interviews with family members, friends, healthcare professionals, and review of available records. The aim of a psychological autopsy is to gain insight into the individual's mental health, potential risk factors, and the events leading up to the suicidal act. It can help in understanding the underlying causes and identifying preventive measures for similar cases in the future.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory module, Topic: Autopsy-1, Sub-topic: Psychological autopsy.","responses":[{"text":"Patients dying in mental hospital","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suicide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Custodial death","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Psychopaths","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16158,"text":"Exhumation is made mandatory in case of which of the following?","explanation":"**Exhumation** is made mandatory in the case of a **magistrate order**. When there is a legal requirement or court order, exhumation may be carried out to exhume a buried body for further investigation, reexamination, or legal proceedings. This could be due to various reasons, such as a suspected crime, the need for further forensic examination, or the resolution of a legal dispute. The decision to exhume a body is typically made by a magistrate or a court of law based on the specific circumstances and legal requirements of the case.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory module, Topic: Autopsy-3, Sub-topic: Procedure of exhumation.","responses":[{"text":"In case of an unclaimed body","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Request of relatives","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"If the medicolegal officer missed something","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magistrate order","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"In case of suspended animation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16160,"text":"A 4-year-old boy presents to the emergency department with complaints of coughing and wheezing after swallowing a 5 rupees coin. The pulmonologist used a bronchoscope to perform foreign body aspiration to remove the coin. What is the most expected place for obstruction?","explanation":"The most expected place for obstruction after swallowing a coin and subsequent foreign body aspiration in a 4-year-old boy is the **right bronchus**.\r\n\r\nThe right bronchus is wider, shorter, and more vertically oriented compared to the left bronchus. This anatomical difference makes it easier for an aspirated object to enter the right bronchus rather than the left bronchus. Therefore, in the majority of cases, when a coin is aspirated, it tends to become lodged in the right bronchus rather than the left bronchus.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 173.","responses":[{"text":"Left bronchus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right bronchus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchioles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16161,"text":"What is found in freshwater drowning?","explanation":"**Freshwater drowning** is characterized by dilution of plasma that may cause rupture of red blood cells, resulting in release of K+ and consequent **potassium excess**. \r\n\r\nThe hyponatremia in freshwater drowning is primarily due to the dilutional effect of the water on sodium levels. The dilution of sodium occurs because freshwater has a lower sodium concentration compared to the body's normal fluid composition. This leads to an osmotic shift, where water moves from the less concentrated extracellular fluid into the more dilute intracellular fluid, including brain cells. As a result, the brain cells swell and can cause various neurological symptoms.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 177.","responses":[{"text":"Less magnesium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium excess","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sodium excess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Less potassium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16162,"text":"Which expectorant acts directly on the airway and through reflex?","explanation":"**Potassium iodide** is an expectorant that acts **directly on the airway** and also through a **reflex mechanism**. \r\n\r\nIt works by increasing the volume and reducing the viscosity of respiratory tract secretions, making it easier to cough up mucus and phlegm. This helps in clearing the airways and promoting easier breathing. \r\n\r\nPotassium iodide is commonly used as an expectorant in conditions such as bronchitis and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Respiratory module, Pharmacology slides, Topic: Antitussives, Sub-topic: Cough expectorants.","responses":[{"text":"Bromhexine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Guaifenesin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcysteine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium iodide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Terpin hydrate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16163,"text":"Which of the following statements about antitussives is correct?","explanation":"**Codeine** is an opioid antitussive that acts on the cough reflex in the brain to suppress coughing. **Naloxone** is an opioid receptor antagonist that can block the effects of opioids, including codeine. If naloxone is administered, it can reverse the effects of codeine and potentially counteract its antitussive properties.","reference":"(1) Dow lecture slides, Respiratory module, Pharmacology slides, Topic: Antitussives, Sub-topic: Cough suppressants.\r\n\r\n(2) Abuse NI on D. Naloxone drugfacts. National Institute on Drug Abuse. Published January 11, 2022. Accessed June 20, 2023. https://nida.nih.gov/publications/drugfacts/naloxone","responses":[{"text":"Dextromethorphan is a mucokinetic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bromhexine is mucokinetic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Codeine is inhibited by naloxone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Guaifenesin is a centrally-acting antitussive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphenhydramine is toxic to infants","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16166,"text":"A negative autopsy is observed in which of the following situations?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Body is in advanced stage of decomposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medical examiner is not skilled","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Penetrating fragment injuries in explosion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasovagal shock and fright","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16169,"text":"Long-term oxygen therapy is initiated in patients at which of the following partial pressures of arterial blood gases?","explanation":"**Long-term oxygen therapy (LTOT)** is initiated in patients with a **partial pressure of arterial oxygen (PaO₂) less than 55 mmHg (or arterial oxygen saturation [SaO₂] less than 88%)** while breathing room air at rest. This is the general threshold for initiating LTOT in patients with chronic respiratory conditions such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).\r\n\r\nLTOT aims to increase the oxygen content in the blood to improve oxygenation and alleviate symptoms in patients with severe hypoxemia. It is typically prescribed for patients who have chronic respiratory failure and impaired gas exchange.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 577.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PaO₂ = 55-102 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PaCO₂ \u003c 35 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PaO₂ \u003c 55 mmHg","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"PaCO₂ \u003c 40 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16170,"text":"Which method is used to diagnose and classify chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)?","explanation":"The method used to diagnose and classify chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is **spirometry**.\r\n\r\n**Spirometry** is a pulmonary function test that measures the amount of air a person can inhale and exhale and the rate at which they can do so. It provides objective measurements of lung function and helps in assessing the presence and severity of airflow limitation, which is a key characteristic of COPD.\r\n\r\nIn spirometry, the forced expiratory volume in one second (FEV1) and the forced vital capacity (FVC) are measured. The FEV1/FVC ratio is then calculated. A reduced FEV1/FVC ratio below a certain threshold (usually less than 0.70) is indicative of airflow limitation, which is a hallmark feature of COPD. The severity of COPD can be further classified based on the post-bronchodilator FEV1 value.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 575.","responses":[{"text":"Methacholine test","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Computerized tomography (CT) scan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spirometry","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Exercise tolerance test (ETT)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest radiograph","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16171,"text":"A non-selective β₂ agonist is given for bronchodilation in asthma. What unwanted side effect can it produce?","explanation":"A non-selective β₂ agonist, when given for bronchodilation in asthma, can produce the unwanted side effect of **tachycardia**.\r\n\r\nβ₂ agonists primarily act on β₂ adrenergic receptors in the airway smooth muscles, leading to **bronchodilation** and relief of asthma symptoms. However, **non-selective β₂ agonists** can also stimulate β₁ adrenergic receptors in the heart, which can result in an **increased heart rate (tachycardia)**. This side effect is more likely to occur with non-selective β₂ agonists compared to selective β₂ agonists, which have a more specific action on the airways and are less likely to affect heart rate.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 84.","responses":[{"text":"Hypotension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Worsening bronchoconstriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Postural hypotension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bradycardia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tachycardia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16172,"text":"A firefighter has failed his yearly fitness exam. His chest x-ray shows no masses or hilar lymphadenopathy but diffuse pulmonary infiltrates with reticular shadowing and honeycombing can be seen. There are no anti-nuclear or anti-Scl-70 antibodies. On spirometry, FEV1 is almost normal and FVC is considerably decreased. What is the patient suffering from?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for the firefighter is **idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF)**.\r\n\r\nIdiopathic pulmonary fibrosis is a chronic and progressive lung disease characterized by the formation of scar tissue (fibrosis) in the lungs. It is of unknown cause (idiopathic) and typically affects individuals over the age of 50. The most common presenting symptom is shortness of breath, which can progress over time. Other symptoms may include a dry cough and fatigue.\r\n\r\nIn IPF, chest X-rays often show diffuse pulmonary infiltrates with reticular shadowing and honeycombing, which are characteristic findings of fibrotic changes in the lungs. The spirometry results mentioned in the scenario also support the diagnosis, as IPF typically shows a decreased forced vital capacity (FVC) due to restrictive lung disease, while the forced expiratory volume in 1 second (FEV1) may be relatively preserved.\r\n\r\nScleroderma and sarcoidosis are other conditions that can cause pulmonary fibrosis, but the absence of anti-nuclear and anti-Scl-70 antibodies in this case makes them less likely. Tuberculosis and Goodpasture syndrome are unrelated to the findings described in the scenario and are not consistent with the presented symptoms and imaging findings.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 489, 535.","responses":[{"text":"Sarcoidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goodpasture syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Scleroderma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16173,"text":"Which two anti-tuberculosis drugs are considered bactericidal?","explanation":"The two anti-tuberculosis drugs that are considered bactericidal are **isoniazid** and **rifampin**.\r\n\r\n**Isoniazid (INH)** is a first-line drug used in the treatment of tuberculosis. It works by inhibiting the synthesis of mycolic acids, which are essential components of the bacterial cell wall. This disruption of cell wall synthesis leads to bacterial death.\r\n\r\n**Rifampin** is another first-line drug used in tuberculosis treatment. It works by inhibiting bacterial RNA synthesis through binding to the bacterial RNA polymerase. This inhibition disrupts the transcription process and ultimately results in bacterial death.\r\n\r\nBoth isoniazid and rifampin are considered **bactericida**l because they directly kill the tuberculous bacteria rather than just inhibiting their growth.","reference":"(1) Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 398.\r\n\r\n(2) Zeng S, Soetaert K, Ravon F, et al. Isoniazid bactericidal activity involves electron transport chain perturbation. Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy. Published February 26, 2019. Accessed June 18, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6395907/","responses":[{"text":"Isoniazid and ethambutol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyrazinamide and ethambutol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoniazid and rifampin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rifampin and streptokinase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16175,"text":"Secondary mycobacterial infection should always be an important consideration in\r\nhuman immunodeficiency virus (HIV)-positive patients who present with pulmonary disease. Which organism is most likely responsible for causing it?","explanation":"***Mycobacterium tuberculosis*** is the causative agent of **tuberculosis (TB)**, which is a bacterial infection primarily affecting the lungs. HIV infection significantly increases the risk of developing active TB disease. HIV weakens the immune system, making individuals more susceptible to opportunistic infections, including mycobacterial infections. In particular, HIV-positive individuals are at an increased risk of reactivating latent tuberculosis infection or acquiring new tuberculosis infections.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 371.\r\n\r\n\r\n(2) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 361, 525.","responses":[{"text":"Mycobacterium marinum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium avium complex","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium bovis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium scrofulaceum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycobacterium tuberculosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16177,"text":"Isoniazid causes anemia and neuritis due to which of the following reasons?","explanation":"**Isoniazid (INH)** causes anemia and neuritis primarily due to its interference with **pyridoxine (vitamin B6) metabolism** and induction of its deficiency.\r\n\r\nIsoniazid is an antituberculosis medication commonly used in the treatment and prevention of tuberculosis. It exerts its antimicrobial effect by inhibiting the synthesis of mycolic acids, which are essential components of the mycobacterial cell wall. However, isoniazid can also interfere with the metabolism of pyridoxine, a vitamin that plays a crucial role in various physiological processes, including the synthesis of neurotransmitters, hemoglobin, and myelin.\r\n\r\nThe use of isoniazid can lead to a deficiency of pyridoxine in the body, which can manifest as **peripheral neuropathy** or **neuritis**.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 415.","responses":[{"text":"Interferes with post-translational modification of proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Induces the production of auto-antibodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Causes demyelination of neurons","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interferes with pyridoxine metabolism and induces its deficiency","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Has toxic effects on red blood cells and neurons","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16178,"text":"A lady presents to the clinic with complaints of fever, purulent cough, and dyspnea. Chest x-ray shows lobar consolidation. What is the most common cause of lobar pneumonia?","explanation":"The most common cause of lobar pneumonia is ***Streptococcus pneumoniae***.\r\n\r\n*Streptococcus pneumoniae*, also known as pneumococcus, is a gram-positive bacterium that commonly causes **lobar pneumonia**. It is responsible for a significant proportion of **community-acquired pneumonia** cases. Lobar pneumonia refers to the infection and inflammation of an entire lobe or a large portion of a lung. The infection typically starts in the alveoli and spreads to involve an entire lobe, leading to consolidation seen on chest x-ray.\r\n\r\nWhile other bacteria such as *Staphylococcus aureus, Haemophilus influenzae*, and *Klebsiella pneumoniae* can also cause pneumonia, Streptococcus pneumoniae is the most common pathogen associated with lobar pneumonia. However, the specific causative agent may vary depending on factors such as the patient's age, underlying health conditions, and geographic location","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 711.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 703.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Klebsiella pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemophilus influenzae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16180,"text":"A newborn baby is in respiratory distress due to the lack of surfactant. Which of the following cells is the reason behind this?","explanation":"The lack of surfactant in a newborn baby leading to respiratory distress is primarily due to the **immaturity or deficiency of pneumocyte type 2 cells**.\r\n\r\nPneumocyte type 2 cells, also known as surfactant-producing cells, are specialized cells found in the alveoli of the lungs. They play a crucial role in the production and secretion of pulmonary surfactant, a substance that helps reduce surface tension within the alveoli and prevents them from collapsing during expiration. Surfactant is composed of lipids, proteins, and other components.\r\n\r\nIn newborn babies, particularly premature infants, the production and secretion of surfactant by the pneumocyte type 2 cells may be insufficient or immature. This can result in **respiratory distress syndrome (RDS)** or neonatal respiratory distress syndrome (NRDS), a condition characterized by difficulty in breathing, rapid breathing, and signs of respiratory distress shortly after birth.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 364.","responses":[{"text":"Pneumocyte type 1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumocyte type 2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dust cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brush cell","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16190,"text":"A 52-year-old man, a heavy smoker, presents to the clinic with complaints of cough, hemoptysis, and weight loss. His chest X-ray shows an ill-defined 0.4 cm mass involving the left hilum of the lung. Bronchial washing shows lymphocyte-like cells. The doctor infers from the biopsy that surgical removal is not helpful in this case. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis in this case is **small cell carcinoma of the lung**.\r\n\r\nSmall cell carcinoma, also known as oat cell carcinoma, is a type of lung cancer that is strongly associated with **heavy smoking**. It typically presents with symptoms such as cough, hemoptysis (coughing up blood), and weight loss. On imaging, small cell carcinoma may appear as a centrally located mass, often involving the hilar region of the lung.\r\n\r\nThe diagnosis of small cell carcinoma is confirmed through biopsy and examination of the tumor cells. In this case, the bronchial washing showing lymphocyte-like cells is suggestive of small cell carcinoma. Small cell carcinoma is a highly malignant tumor with a tendency for early metastasis, and it is known for its aggressive nature.\r\n\r\nSurgical removal is generally not the treatment of choice for small cell carcinoma due to its propensity for early spread and involvement of regional lymph nodes. Instead, treatment typically involves a combination of chemotherapy and radiation therapy.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 718-719.\r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 705.","responses":[{"text":"Small cell carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16191,"text":"What instrument is used to assess the volume of inspired and expired air?","explanation":"The instrument used to assess the volume of inspired and expired air is called a **spirometer**.\r\n\r\nA spirometer is a device that measures **lung volumes** and **capacities** by assessing the flow and volume of air during breathing. It is commonly used in pulmonary function testing to evaluate lung function and diagnose respiratory conditions such as asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and restrictive lung diseases.\r\n\r\nDuring spirometry, the individual breathes into the spirometer, which records various parameters, including tidal volume (the volume of air inhaled and exhaled during normal breathing), inspiratory reserve volume (the additional volume that can be inhaled after a normal inhalation), expiratory reserve volume (the additional volume that can be exhaled after a normal exhalation), and vital capacity (the maximum volume of air that can be exhaled after a maximum inhalation). These measurements provide valuable information about lung function and can help in diagnosing and monitoring respiratory conditions.","reference":"Lamb K, Theodore D, Bhutta BS. Spirometry. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 19, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560526/","responses":[{"text":"Tonometer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial blood gas (ABG) analyzer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oximeter","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spirometer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphygmomanometer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16192,"text":"What findings suggest that a pleural effusion has become empyema?","explanation":"**Empyema** is a condition characterized by the presence of **pus in the pleural cavity**, which is the space between the lungs and the chest wall. In empyema, the pleural fluid becomes infected and inflammatory cells, bacteria, and debris accumulate, leading to the formation of pus.\r\n\r\nGlucose levels in pleural fluid can help differentiate between different types of pleural effusions. In empyema, the pleural fluid is often characterized by **low glucose levels (less than 60 mg/dL)**. This is because the infecting bacteria consume the glucose present in the pleural fluid as a nutrient source.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, other types of pleural effusions, such as parapneumonic effusions or transudative effusions, typically have higher glucose levels (more than 60 mg/dL) in the pleural fluid.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 564.","responses":[{"text":"Pleural LDH less than serum LDH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose more than 60 mg/dL in pleural fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose less than 60 mg/dL in pleural fluid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"pH \u003e 7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low serum glucose","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16196,"text":"A man who works as a laborer in the ship-breaking industry comes to the outpatient department with progressive dyspnea and pleural plaques in both lungs. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for the man who works in the ship-breaking industry and presents with progressive dyspnea and pleural plaques in both lungs is **asbestosis**.\r\n\r\nAsbestosis is a lung disease caused by long-term exposure to asbestos fibers. **Ship-breaking** involves working with materials that may contain asbestos, such as insulation and fireproofing materials used in older ships. Inhalation of asbestos fibers over time can lead to the development of asbestosis.\r\n\r\nThe characteristic features of asbestosis include **progressive dyspnea (shortness of breath)** and the presence of **pleural plaques**, which are areas of fibrous thickening on the pleura (the lining of the lungs). These pleural plaques are a typical finding in asbestosis and can be seen on imaging studies, such as chest X-rays.\r\n\r\nIdiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, ozone exposure, and silicosis are other conditions that can cause respiratory symptoms and lung damage, but given the occupational history of ship-breaking and the presence of pleural plaques, asbestosis is the most likely diagnosis in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 695.","responses":[{"text":"Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Silicosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ozone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asbestosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16221,"text":"A child presents to the clinic with the complaint of severe chronic sinusitis. He is found to have increased sodium chloride concentration on a sweat test. He also had\r\na problem with meconium expulsion at birth. Which of the following conditions is he at risk of developing?","explanation":"The child is at risk of developing **bronchiectasis**.\r\n\r\nBronchiectasis is a condition characterized by **permanent dilation** and **damage to the bronchial tubes**, leading to chronic respiratory symptoms such as cough, sputum production, and recurrent respiratory infections. It can be associated with **cystic fibrosis**, a genetic disorder that affects the production and function of mucus, sweat, and digestive juices. The increased sodium chloride concentration on the sweat test suggests the possibility of cystic fibrosis in this case.\r\n\r\nIn cystic fibrosis, the abnormal mucus production can obstruct the airways, leading to recurrent infections, inflammation, and damage to the bronchial walls. Over time, this can result in bronchiectasis, which is a common complication of cystic fibrosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 467, 470, 687.","responses":[{"text":"Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumocystis carinii","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiectasis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesothelioma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16222,"text":"According to the transtheoretical model (TTM), what does precontemplation mean?","explanation":"According to the transtheoretical model (TTM), **precontemplation** refers to the stage in which an individual is **not yet acknowledging that there is a problem** and has no intention of changing their behavior in the foreseeable future. In this stage, the person may be unaware or in denial of the need for change and may not see any negative consequences associated with their current behavior.","reference":"Raihan N, Cogburn M. Stages of change theory. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 21, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556005/","responses":[{"text":"Getting ready for change","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Not acknowledging that there is a problem","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The person has acknowledged the problem but is not ready to change his behaviour yet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Change in behaviour","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16223,"text":"A 55-year-old woman has had progressive dyspnea and a dry cough for many days. She has also experienced weight loss. She does not smoke and has also joined a church lately. Imaging studies show a peripheral mass. After carrying out thorough investigations, the doctor decides to resect it. What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The most likely diagnosis for the peripheral mass in the lung of a non-smoking woman with progressive dyspnea, dry cough, and weight loss is **adenocarcinoma**.\r\n\r\n**Adenocarcinoma** is a type of non-small cell lung cancer that commonly presents with **peripheral lung masses**. It is the most common type of lung cancer in **non-smokers** and can occur in both men and women. Adenocarcinomas are often associated with symptoms such as cough, dyspnea, weight loss, and can be accompanied by systemic symptoms.\r\n\r\nSmall cell carcinoma is typically associated with a history of smoking and presents as central lung masses. Large cell carcinoma is another type of non-small cell lung cancer, but it is less common and typically presents as peripheral masses. Mesothelioma is a cancer of the mesothelial cells lining the pleural cavity and is associated with asbestos exposure. Squamous cell carcinoma is another type of non-small cell lung cancer that is often centrally located.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 716-718.","responses":[{"text":"Small cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesothelioma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16224,"text":"A 40-year-old woman comes to the clinic with a cough and mucopurulent\r\nsputum. She has been having repeated infections since childhood. Chest x-ray shows\r\ndilation of bronchi. What is the likely pathogenesis of her disease?","explanation":"The likely pathogenesis of the woman's disease, characterized by repeated infections, mucopurulent sputum, and bronchial dilation seen on chest x-ray, is **bronchial wall damage due to recurrent inflammation**.\r\n\r\nThis presentation is consistent with **bronchiectasis**, a condition characterized by irreversible dilation and damage to the bronchi. The repeated infections lead to chronic inflammation of the bronchial walls, resulting in their weakening and subsequent dilation. The damaged bronchi are less effective in clearing mucus and pathogens, leading to the accumulation of mucopurulent sputum.\r\n\r\nCongenital defects in the bronchial wall can be associated with bronchiectasis, but they are not typically the most common cause. Macrophage-mediated injury and cellular responses against nitric oxide are not commonly implicated in the pathogenesis of bronchiectasis.\r\n\r\nAlpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency is a genetic condition that can lead to lung disease, including emphysema, but it is not directly associated with bronchiectasis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 687.","responses":[{"text":"Bronchial wall damage due to recurrent inflammation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Congenital defect in bronchial wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrophage-mediated injury","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cellular response against nitric oxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16225,"text":"A 69-year-old man with type 2 diabetes mellitus presents to the clinic with a non-productive cough and chest pain. The doctor suspects pneumonia. Chest X-ray shows patchy lung infiltrates. Cultures are inconclusive. The specimen has been sent for molecular testing. What is the most likely cause of his disease?","explanation":"The most likely cause of the patient's disease in this case is ***Mycoplasma pneumoniae***. ***Mycoplasma pneumoniae*** is a common cause of **atypical pneumonia**, also known as walking pneumonia. It is characterized by **non-productive cough, chest pain**, and **patchy lung infiltrates** on chest X-ray. *Mycoplasma pneumoniae* is a bacterium that lacks a cell wall, making it resistant to many antibiotics that target cell wall synthesis. Cultures are often inconclusive, and molecular testing methods, such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR), are commonly used to identify the organism. \r\n\r\n*Neisseria meningitidis, Streptococcus pneumoniae, Staphylococcus aureus*, and *Haemophilus influenzae* are also potential causes of pneumonia but are less likely based on the clinical presentation described.","reference":"Abdulhadi B, Kiel J. Mycoplasma pneumonia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed June 21, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430780/","responses":[{"text":"Haemophilus influenzae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycoplasma pneumoniae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcus pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria meningitidis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16226,"text":"A 38-year-old male presents to the clinic with a complaint of episodes of cough and wheezing. The episodes are recurrent and have been happening for 5 years in winter and with mild respiratory infections. He is normal between the episodes. There is no family history of asthma or allergy. His chest radiographs are normal. IgE and WBC\r\ncount is normal. Which of the following is the cause of his condition?","explanation":"The most likely cause of the patient's condition is **hyperreactive airways due to inflammation from viral infection**. The recurrent episodes of cough and wheezing associated with mild respiratory infections and occurring mainly in winter suggest a pattern consistent with viral-induced asthma or viral-induced bronchial hyperresponsiveness. **Viral respiratory infections** can cause inflammation in the airways, leading to **increased bronchial reactivity** and symptoms such as cough and wheezing. This condition is often seen in individuals with no family history of asthma or allergy and normal IgE and WBC count. \r\n\r\nHistamine release by mast cells and production of major basic protein by eosinophils are associated with allergic asthma and eosinophilic asthma, respectively, but they do not match the clinical presentation described in this case. \r\n\r\nAspergillosis is a fungal infection and not likely to be the cause in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 683.","responses":[{"text":"Hyperresponsiveness of airways to aspergillosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperreactive airways due to inflammation from viral infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine release by mast cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Production of major basic protein by eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16227,"text":"A 40-year-old man with a history of smoking presents with a persistent cough. On examination, he is cyanosed and is later diagnosed as a case of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). Which material is responsible for damaging pulmonary tissue in this condition?","explanation":"In **chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)**, the main material responsible for damaging pulmonary tissue is **elastase**. Elastase is an enzyme that breaks down elastin, which is a major component of the lung tissue. In individuals with COPD, there is an imbalance between elastase and its inhibitor, alpha-1-antitrypsin. This imbalance leads to increased activity of elastase, causing **destruction of lung tissue** and **loss of elasticity**. This contributes to the characteristic airflow limitation and lung damage seen in COPD.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 680-681.","responses":[{"text":"Metalloproteinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha-1-antitrypsin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagenase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16239,"text":"What is the most common hazard of autopsy?","explanation":"The most common hazard of autopsy is **cuts and pinpricks**. During the autopsy procedure, sharp instruments such as scalpels and needles are used, increasing the risk of accidental cuts or punctures to the individuals performing the autopsy. These injuries can potentially lead to exposure to bloodborne pathogens and infectious materials, including viruses, bacteria, and other microorganisms present in the body being examined. Proper precautions, including the use of personal protective equipment and adherence to safety protocols, are essential to minimize the risk of such injuries during autopsies.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 124.","responses":[{"text":"Viral infections like hepatitis B and AIDS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiation burns","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corneal ulcers from bone dust","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrocution by faulty machinery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cuts and pinpricks","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":16257,"text":"A research mentor asks his students to write research proposals that are feasible. What does he mean by feasible?","explanation":"When a research mentor asks his students to write research proposals that are feasible, he means that the proposals should be focused on **resource management**.\r\n\r\n**Feasibility** in research refers to the practicality and achievability of the proposed study within the available resources, including time, funding, equipment, and personnel. A feasible research proposal takes into consideration the limitations and constraints of the research setting and ensures that the proposed study can be realistically conducted with the available resources.\r\n\r\nWhile relevance in the scientific community and novelty are important aspects of research, feasibility specifically emphasizes the practical aspects of conducting the study. It ensures that the research project can be successfully executed given the available resources, thus increasing the likelihood of its completion and obtaining meaningful results.","reference":"Finer: a research framework | elsevier author services blog. Elsevier Author Services - Articles. Published May 25, 2020. Accessed June 22, 2023. https://scientific-publishing.webshop.elsevier.com/research-process/finer-research-framework/","responses":[{"text":"Perfect objective","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Relevant in the scientific community","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Resource management","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Novel","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a